@node UNREG "Unregistered evaluation version"
@toc MAIN

Registered vs. unregistered
---------------------------

The  unregistered  evaluation  version of Reflex does not differ a lot from
the  registered  version.  Only  a  few  features  are  only  available  to
registered  users.  These  features will be enabled if you register Reflex.
Please refer to the @{" How to register " LINK REGISTER} section of this guide.

By  registering  you will receive a @{" keyfile " LINK KEYFILE}, which you name 'Reflex.key'
and  place  in  the  'PROGDIR:'  of  Reflex, 's:' or according to a KEYPATH
environment variable. This keyfile will unlock the features disabled in the
unregistered evaluation version.

This  keyfile  gives the registered user access to the features disabled in
the unregistered evaluation version. The features that will be available to
the  registered  users  include (negate this if you would like to know what
features are disabled in the unregistered version):

 - In  the  registered  version  Reflex becomes an @{" ARexx port " LINK AREXXPORT}. With more
   than  100  @{" ARexx commands " LINK AREXXDOC}  Reflex  has  got  a  very  powerful  ARexx
   interface  allowing  the  registered  user  to automatically process the
   contents  of  the  outbound  directory, @{" delete " LINK F_D} files, @{" re-destinate " LINK F_CD}
   files, @{" change status " LINK F_CS}, automatic @{" attaching " LINK AT} of files etc. Some ARexx
   scripts for Reflex are already included in the Reflex distribution.

 - If you are familar with Nico Franþois' excellent Fido tosser/editor Spot
   you  might  know, that Spot will attempt to execute an ARexx script when
   you select certain gadgets instead of its normal function.

   I  have  found this feature very nice - so nice I've made Reflex support
   this  feature  too. It enables the user to configure the function of all
   gadgets and some menu items in the @{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI}.

   This  is  managed by executing @{" '_<gadget>.flex' scripts " LINK _AREXX}, which Reflex
   will search  for  in  the  @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.  E.g. Reflex will execute
   the  ARexx  script '_Delete.flex' if it exists when the user selects the
   @{" 'Delete' " LINK F_D} gadget.  If the script doesn't exist Reflex will perform the
   normal  function  of  the  gadget  - just as it does in the unregistered
   evaluation version.

 - In  the  registered  version  of  Reflex you all of a sudden can use the
   @{" ARexx menu " LINK FM_A}  for  more  than  its  good  looking.  In the unregistered
   version   you   can   configure   the  ARexx  menu  using  the  @{" ARexx " LINK CFGR}
   @{" configuration " LINK CFGR} window, but attempts to execute the scripts through the
   ARexx  menu  will  only  result in the "Unregistered evaluation version"
   requester.  When  you  become  a  registered user it will be possible to
   lauch ARexx scripts from within Reflex.

 - @{" Attaching " LINK AT} of  files  will  now  be done to the correct system. In the
   unregistered evaluation version file attaching does not work to its full
   extent;   true  attaching  is  not  performed  -  only  a  demonstration
   attaching   to   node  12:5/70  can  be  performed  if  wished.  In  the
   unregistered  version  attaching is done correctly - except it is always
   done  to node 12:5/70. As a registered user of Reflex you will naturally
   be  able to attach to all known and unknown systems throughout the whole
   wide world.

 - The  same  pertains  to @{" file request " LINK FR} of files.  Now in the registered
   version  it  can  be  done  at  all  known  and  unknown systems. In the
   unregistered evaluation version only a demonstration request can be made
   at node 12:5/70.

 - Naturally  the  "Unregistered  evaluation  version"  requesters  will no
   longer  appear  -  and  just  as  important  -  no  "Registered version"
   requesters  will  appear. Your registration number and name will also be
   shown in the About requester. Be it of any use.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Reflex main window - gadgets and menus
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node FLEXGUI "Reflex main window"
@toc MAIN

Reflex main window
------------------

This  is  the  main  window of Reflex. The main window is your interface to
your outbound directory. In that Reflex is an outbound manager the listview
displaying  the  contents  of  your outbound directory occupies most of the
window.

Below  the  listview  are  ten  gadgets  primarily  used  to manipulate the
contents of the outbound directory.

The main window looks a bit like:

   @{"                        Listview                       " LINK F_L}

   @{"     Info    " LINK F_I}@{"    Delete   " LINK F_D}@{"    Attach   " LINK F_A }@{"     Freq    " LINK F_F}
   @{"       Change Status       " LINK F_CS}@{"     Change Destination    " LINK F_CD}
   @{"     Poll    " LINK F_P}@{" Maintenance " LINK F_M}@{"    Rescan   " LINK F_R}@{"     Quit    " LINK F_Q}

Depending on the contents of the listview and the placement of the listview
marker some gadgets will be enabled and some will be disabled (ghosted).

A menu is also attached to this window. The primary reason for this menu is
for  you  to access the configuration windows - quite a few of the features
will  not become apparent until you have examined the configuration windows
-  I take it you will not be reading the documentation unless everything is
at fire.

In the menu bar you will find the following menu items:

   @{" Project          " LINK FM_P} @{" Edit       " LINK FM_E} @{" Settings     " LINK FM_S} @{" ARexx             " LINK FM_A}
   ======================================================================
   @{" Print            " LINK FM_PP} @{" Copy entry " LINK FM_ECE} @{" Files...     " LINK FM_SF} @{" Execute script... " LINK FM_AES}
   ------------------- @{" Copy list  " LINK FM_ECA} @{" Mailer...    " LINK FM_SM} --------------------
   @{" About            " LINK FM_PA}               @{" GUI...       " LINK FM_SGUI} @{" >> user <<        " LINK FM_AS}
   @{" Acknowledgements " LINK FM_PAA}               @{" General...   " LINK FM_SG} @{" >> user <<        " LINK FM_AS}
   -------------------               @{" Deletion...  " LINK FM_SD}
   @{" Hide             " LINK FM_PH}               @{" Attaching... " LINK FM_SA}
   @{" Quit             " LINK FM_PQ}               @{" Nodebook...  " LINK FM_SN}
                                     @{" ARexx...     " LINK FM_SRx}
                                     ---------------
                                     @{" Save         " LINK FM_SSS}

Keyboard shortcuts are available for all gadgets and most menu items.

Apart  from  the gadgets and menu items you can move the listview marker up
and  down  - naturally. If you double click an entry in the listview or hit
the   return   key   Reflex  will  attempt  to  execute  the  ARexx  script
'_Listview.flex'  located  in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}. This script is one of
the  so-called @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX}. This feature is not available in
the @{" unregistered evaluation version " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_I "Main window 'Info' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Info' gadget
-------------------------

Not much to say about this gadget. When you select the 'Info' gadget Reflex
will  display  what  information  it  knows  about the current entry in the
listview.  The  extent  of information differs from one @{" type of entry " LINK ENTRYTYPES} to
another.

Information  displayed  include filename, size, date, receiving system, its
name,  status  of  the  entry,  its  type,  name of flow file in which it's
listed,  its verbatim entry in the flow file, and what the mailer should do
with  the file after it has been sent. Not all information is available for
all @{" entry types " LINK ENTRYTYPES}.

The 'Info' gadget will be disabled if the listview is empty.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}SHOWINFO@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget.  This ARexx script
is named '_Info.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_D "Main window 'Delete' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Delete' gadget
---------------------------

When  you select the 'Delete' gadget the current entry in the listview will
be  deleted. In other words the current entry will no longer be sent to the
receiving system.

Depending upon the @{" type on entry " LINK ENTRYTYPES} the file deletion differs a bit:

 - Is  the current entry an @{" orphan or empty file " LINK ENTRYTYPES} it will be delete right
   away  -  no  chance  for  you to reconsider you choice. Orphan and empty
   files are normally files you don't want in your outbound directory.

 - @{" Flow file entries of missing files " LINK ENTRYTYPES} will also be deleted right away.

 - @{" Mail " LINK ENTRYTYPES},  compressed  and  uncompressed,  will  be deleted when you have
   confirmed the deletion.

 - @{" Attached files " LINK ENTRYTYPES}  will  be  removed  from  the  flow file when you have
   confirmed   the  removal  of  the  entry.  Reflex  also  gives  you  the
   possibility of actually deleting the files as well.

 - Your @{" requests " LINK ENTRYTYPES} at other systems are deleted after your confirmation.

 - @{" Requests at your system " LINK ENTRYTYPES} are handled just like attached files.

Some  might  not  find  this satisfying - some want confirmation before all
deletions,  and  some  probably  doesn't  care if files or mail are deleted
accidentially.  I've  been aware of that, and the above procedure is my own
preference.

Attached  to  the  'Delete'  gadgets  is a @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} which
naturally  is  named  '_Delete.flex'  and  must  be located in the @{" ARexx " LINK CFGF_AD}
@{" directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.  Using  this  feature  of Reflex enables you to easily prompt
with  a  requester  before  each  deletion - or maybe even password protect
deletion  so your cat accidentially don't delete files when it walks across
your   keyboard.   A  plurality  of possibilities are available through the
@{"ARexx  port "  LINK AREXXPORT} and the @{" '_<gadget>.flex' scripts " LINK _AREXX}.

The ARexx command corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}DELETEENTRY@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

The 'Delete' gadget will be disabled if the listview is empty.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_A "Main window 'Attach' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Attach' gadget
---------------------------

Selecting  the 'Attach' gadget simply brings the @{" Attach requester " LINK AT} forth.
Does  the current entry in the listview include a Fido address this address
will be the one the Attach requester opens with.

The 'Attach' gadget ought to be enabled all the time.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to  this gadget is named @{b}REQUESTATTACH@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is named '_Attach.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_F "Main window 'Freq' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Freq' gadget
-------------------------

Selecting the 'Freq' gadget simply brings the @{" Freq requester " LINK FR} forth. Does
the  current entry in the listview include a Fido address this address will
be the one the Freq requester opens with.

The 'Freq' gadget ought to be enabled all the time.

The ARexx command corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}REQUESTFREQ@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is named '_Freq.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_CS "Main window 'Change Status' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Change Status' gadget
----------------------------------

Selecting  the 'Change Status' gadget brings the @{" Change status requester " LINK CS}
forth.  It  is  naturally  only  possible  to change status of files with a
@{i}Normal@{ui}, @{i}Crash@{ui}, @{i}Hold@{ui} or @{i}Direct@{ui} flavour.

It  is  furthermore  possible  to change status to one of the four flavours
above on a @{" request flow file " LINK ENTRYTYPES} (.RLO file).

The Status requester will open with the flavour of the current entry.

The  'Change Status'  gadget  is  enabled  when the current entry has got a
@{i}Normal@{ui},  @{i}Crash@{ui}, @{i}Hold@{ui} or @{i}Direct@{ui} flavour or the current entry is listed in a
request flow file.

The  ARexx command corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}CHANGEENTRYSTATUS@{ub}.
See   also   the   ARexx   commands   @{b}SETENTRYSTATUS@{ub},   @{b}REQUESTSTATUS@{ub},  and
@{b}GETENTRYSTATUS@{ub}. Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is named '_ChangeStatus.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_R "Main window 'Rescan' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Rescan' gadget
---------------------------

When  you  select  the  'Rescan'  gadget  your  outbound  directory will be
rescanned.  An outbound rescan ought to be performed frequently.

The  outbound  directory rescanning contains minor flaws whose result might
be  that  the  rescan fails which ought to result in an empty listview - an
empty listview could also be because your outbound directory is empty. This
rescanning  problem  will  hopefully  be solved in a future release - until
then just rescan again until it succeeds.

Depending  upon your settings @{" maintenance " LINK F_M} might be performed right after
the  rescanning.  In the @{" Deletion configuration " LINK DCFG} window you can configure
Reflex  to  perform  maintenance  right  after each rescan or only when you
actually perform a maintenance.

The 'Rescan' gadget ought to be enabled all the time.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to  this gadget is named @{b}RESCAN@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is named '_Rescan.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_P "Main window 'Poll' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Poll' gadget
-------------------------

When  you select the 'Poll' gadget Reflex will attempt to lauch your mailer
for calling the system of the current entry in the listview.

You  are  able  to configure polling through Reflex in various ways through
the  @{" Mailer configuration " LINK CFGM}  and  the  @{" Nodebook " LINK CFGN}.  Please refer to these
sections for more details.

The  'Poll'  gadget  will  be enabled if the current entry contains an Fido
address  of  a  receiving  system. The 'Poll' gadget will be disabled if no
@{" poll command " LINK CFGM_PC} is specified in the @{" Mailer configuration " LINK CFGM} window.

The ARexx command corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}POLLENTRY@{ub}. See also
the   @{b}POLL@{ub}  ARexx  command.  Please  refer  to  the  accompanying  @{" ARexx " LINK AREXXDOC}
@{" documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is named '_Poll.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

If  a  '_Poll.flex' script exists the 'Poll' gadget will be enabled all the
time.  Please  make your '_Poll.flex' ARexx scripts support a current entry
with  no  valid  Fido  address  available.  The '_Poll.flex' script will be
locked  and can therefore not be deleted or edited while Reflex is running.
This feature only applies to the registered version.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_CD "Main window 'Change Destination' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Change Destination' gadget
---------------------------------------

Selecting  the 'Change Destination' gadget brings the @{" Change destination " LINK CD}
@{" requester " LINK CD} forth.  It is naturally only possible to change destination of
files with a valid Fido address.

The Address requester will open with the address of the current entry.

The 'Change Destination' gadget is enabled when the current entry has got a
valid Fido address.

The ARexx command corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}CHANGEENTRYADDRESS@{ub}.
See   also   the   ARexx   commands  @{b}SETENTRYADDRESS@{ub},  @{b}REQUESTADDRESS@{ub},  and
@{b}GETENTRYADDRESS@{ub}. Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is  named  '_ChangeDestination.flex'  and  must  be located in the @{" ARexx " LINK CFGF_AD}
@{" directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_M "Main window 'Maintenance' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Maintenance' gadget
--------------------------------

When  you select the 'Maintenance' gadget Reflex will perform a maintenance
on  your  outbound  directory.  Reflex  will perform a rescan to update its
outbound directory information before the maintenance is performed.

At  maintenance empty files, orphan files, and flow file entries of missing
files will be deleted according to the @{" Deletion configuration " LINK DCFG} settings.

The 'Maintenance' gadget will be enabled if your have ticked one or more of
the file types in the @{" Deletion configuration " LINK DCFG} window.

The ARexx command corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}MAINTENANCE@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is named '_Maintenance.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_Q "Main window 'Quit' gadget"
@toc FLEXGUI

Main window 'Quit' gadget
-------------------------

If  you  want  to quit Reflex select the 'Quit' gadget. If you have changed
the settings without saving Reflex will prompt you with a requester.

The 'Quit' gadget is enabled at all times.

The  ARexx command corresponding to this gadget is named @{b}QUIT@{ub}. Please refer
to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget. This ARexx script
is named '_Quit.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node F_L "The main window listview"
@toc FLEXGUI

The main window listview
------------------------

The  listview  is  sort of your eye to the outbound directory. The listview
lists  the  contents of the outbound directory and the contents of the flow
files giving you a clear sight into mail and files leaving your system.

The listview is updated when a @{" rescan " LINK F_R} is performed.

The listview is separated into five columns.


@{b}Address@{ub}

First  column  is  named  @{b}Address@{ub} and contains the address of the receiving
system.  This  address  is subtracted from the filenames of mail packets or
flow  files  in  the  outbound directory. Most @{" entry types " LINK ENTRYTYPES} all contain a
Fido address.

Instead  of a Fido address this column might contain an 'Empty' or 'Orphan'
statement.  It  means that this @{" entry type " LINK ENTRYTYPES} is an empty file or an orphan
file.

The address might be truncated if it is too wide.


@{b}System@{ub}

The  second  column  is named @{b}System@{ub} and contains the name of the receiving
system.  Reflex  uses the @{" TrapList nodelist library " LINK TRAPLIST} to obtain the system
name from the nodelist.

'Illegal address' means the address for some reason is illegal. Your tosser
or other software ought not produce such files with illegal addresses.

'Unlisted system'  means  the address is not listed in any of the nodelists
Reflex can access through the @{" TrapList nodelist library " LINK TRAPLIST}.

If  you don't have a compiled nodelist it will be listed with a '-' instead
of a system name. Empty files and orphan files with no receiving system are
also listed with a '-'.

The system name might be truncated if it is too wide.


@{b}Filename@{ub}

Third  column  is  named  @{b}Filename@{ub}.  For  most  @{" entry types " LINK ENTRYTYPES}  this column
contains  the  name  of  the file to send to the receiving system. For file
requests the column contain the name of the request.

The filename might be truncated if it is too wide.


@{b}Status@{ub}

The  fourth  column  is  named  @{b}Status@{ub}. Some might like to call this column
'flavour' since it displays the flavour, @{i}Normal@{ui}, @{i}Crash@{ui}, @{i}Hold@{ui} or @{i}Direct@{ui}, of
the  file  to  send. The flavour is displayed in the @{b}Status@{ub} column for most
@{" entry types " LINK ENTRYTYPES},  but  for  file requests and requests at your system Reflex
displays @{i}Freq@{ui} and @{i}Req@{ui}, respectively.


@{b}Size@{ub}

The  last  and  fifth  column  is named @{b}Size@{ub} and displays the filesize. The
filesize is displayed for all @{" entry types " LINK ENTRYTYPES} except for file requests where
the filesize naturally is unknown.


In  a  future  release  the  format  of the listview will hopefully be user
definable.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_P "The 'Project' menu"
@toc FLEXGUI

The 'Project' menu
------------------

The 'Project' menu contains some of the more boring possibilities. The menu
contains the following menu items:

   @{" Print            " LINK FM_PP} 
   -------------------
   @{" About            " LINK FM_PA}
   @{" Acknowledgements " LINK FM_PAA}
   -------------------
   @{" Hide             " LINK FM_PH}
   @{" Quit             " LINK FM_PQ}

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_PP "'Project' menu item 'Print'"
@toc FM_P

'Project' menu item 'Print'
---------------------------

Selecting  this  menu  item  will print the contents of the listview on the
printer (PRT:).

Beware  - no prompting before printing will occur, so if your printer isn't
online Reflex might hang until the system decides to continue.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding to this menu item is named @{b}PRINT@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX} is attached to this gadget.  This ARexx script
is named '_Print.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}. Using
the  '_Print.flex'  script  you  can  configure Reflex to prompt you before
printing if you tend to forget turning the printer on.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_PA "'Project' menu item 'About'"
@toc FM_P

'Project' menu item 'About'
---------------------------

Selecting  this  menu  item  will  display  the  About requester. The About
requester  displays  copyright  information,  and in the registered version
registration number and the name of the registered user.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to  this  menu item is named @{b}SHOWABOUT@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_PAA "'Project' menu item 'Acknowledgements'"
@toc FM_P

'Project' menu item 'Acknowledgements'
--------------------------------------

Selecting  this menu item will display the Acknowledgements requester. This
requester  mentions  the libraries Reflex uses apart from the ones supplied
by Commodore, and some linkable code compiled into Reflex.

See the @{" Acknowledgement " LINK ACK} section of this guide for more information.

The   ARexx   command   corresponding   to   this   menu   item   is  named
@{b}SHOWACKNOWLEDGEMENT@{ub}. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_PH "'Project' menu item 'Hide'"
@toc FM_P

'Project' menu item 'Hide'
--------------------------

Selecting  this  menu  item  will hide the Reflex' GUI. Use the Commodities
Exchange program or the @{" popup hotkey " LINK CFGG_HP} to display the GUI again.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to this menu item is named @{b}HIDEGUI@{ub}. See
also @{b}SHOWGUI@{ub}. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_PQ "'Project' menu item 'Quit'"
@toc FM_P

'Project' menu item 'Quit'
--------------------------

Selecting  the 'Quit' gadget quits Reflex. If you have changed the settings
without  saving  Reflex  will  prompt  you with a requester. This menu item
performs the same function as the @{" 'Quit' gadget " LINK F_Q}.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to this menu item is named @{b}QUIT@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

A  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' script " LINK _AREXX}  is  attached  to  this menu item. This ARexx
script is named '_Quit.flex' and must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx  commands  and  '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_E "The 'Edit' menu"
@toc FLEXGUI

The 'Edit' menu
---------------

The  'Edit'  menu  contains a couple of ways of copying the contents of the
listview  to  the  clipboard  buffer.  The menu contains the following menu
items:

   @{" Copy entry " LINK FM_ECE}
   @{" Copy list  " LINK FM_ECA}

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_ECE "'Edit' menu item 'Copy entry'"
@toc FM_E

'Edit' menu item 'Copy entry'
-----------------------------

Selecting  the  'Copy  entry'  menu  item  copies  the current entry in the
listview to the clipboard.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding to this menu item is named @{b}COPYENTRY@{ub}. An
alias  for  this  command  is  @{b}CLIPENTRY@{ub}.  Please refer to the accompanying
@{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_ECA "'Edit' menu item 'Copy list'"
@toc FM_E

'Edit' menu item 'Copy list'
----------------------------

Seleting  the  'Copy list' menu item copies the contents of the listview to
the clipboard. Each entry will be followed by a line feed.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to this menu item is named @{b}COPYLIST@{ub}. An
alias  for  this  command  is  @{b}CLIPLIST@{ub}.  Please  refer to the accompanying
@{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_S "The 'Settings' menu"
@toc FLEXGUI

The 'Settings' menu
-------------------

The  'Settings'  menu  contains  your  entry point to all the configuration
windows. The menu contains the following menu items:

   @{" Files...     " LINK FM_SF}
   @{" Mailer...    " LINK FM_SM}
   @{" GUI...       " LINK FM_SGUI}
   @{" General...   " LINK FM_SG}
   @{" Deletion...  " LINK FM_SD}
   @{" Attaching... " LINK FM_SA}
   @{" Nodebook...  " LINK FM_SN}
   @{" ARexx...     " LINK FM_SRx}
   ---------------
   @{" Save         " LINK FM_SSS}

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SF "'Settings' menu item 'Files...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'Files...'
-------------------------------

This  menu  item  brings  forth  the @{" Files configuration " LINK CFGF} window. In this
configuration window you configure paths and filenames for Reflex to use.

If you have made changes in the Files configuration window they will not be
saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to  this  menu item is named @{b}EDITFILES@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SM "'Settings' menu item 'Mailer...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'Mailer...'
--------------------------------

This  menu  item  brings  forth the @{" Mailer configuration " LINK CFGM} window. In this
configuration window you configure settings concerning the interaction with
your mailer.

If  you  have made changes in the Mailer configuration window they will not
be saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to  this menu item is named @{b}EDITMAILER@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SGUI "'Settings' menu item 'GUI...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'GUI...'
-----------------------------

This  menu  item  brings  forth  the  @{" GUI configuration " LINK CGUI}  window. In this
configuration  window  you  configure settings concerning the appearance of
the GUI, @{" QuickHelp " LINK QUICKHELP} and progress requesters.

If  you  have made changes in the GUI configuration window they will not be
saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx command corresponding to this menu item is named @{b}EDITGUI@{ub}. Please
refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SG "'Settings' menu item 'General...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'General...'
---------------------------------

This  menu  item  brings forth the @{" General configuration " LINK CFGG} window. In this
configuration   window   you   specify   hotkeys  and  settings  concerning
rescanning.

If  you have made changes in the General configuration window they will not
be saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to this menu item is named @{b}EDITGENERAL@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SD "'Settings' menu item 'Deletion...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'Deletion...'
----------------------------------

This  menu  item brings forth the @{" Deletion configuration " LINK DCFG} window. In this
configuration  window  you  decide  which types of files Reflex must delete
when performing a maintenance.

If you have made changes in the Deletion configuration window they will not
be saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding to this menu item is named @{b}EDITDELETION@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SA "'Settings' menu item 'Attaching...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'Attaching...'
-----------------------------------

This  menu item brings forth the @{" Attaching configuration " LINK CFGA} window. In this
configuration window you are able to configure the default settings for the
@{" Attach requester " LINK AT}.

If  you  have  made changes in the Attaching configuration window they will
not be saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx  command corresponding to this menu item is named @{b}EDITATTACHING@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SN "'Settings' menu item 'Nodebook...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'Nodebook...'
----------------------------------

This  menu  item brings forth the @{" Nodebook configuration " LINK CFGN} window. In this
configuration window you are able to configure special settings for certain
nodes.

If you have made changes in the Nodebook configuration window they will not
be saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding to this menu item is named @{b}EDITNODEBOOK@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SRx "'Settings' menu item 'ARexx...'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'ARexx...'
-------------------------------

This  menu  item  brings  forth  the @{" ARexx configuration " LINK CFGR} window. In this
configuration window you are configure the @{" ARexx menu " LINK FM_A}.

If you have made changes in the ARexx configuration window they will not be
saved until you have selected the @{" Save menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding  to  this  menu item is named @{b}EDITAREXX@{ub}.
Please refer to the accompanying @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_SSS "'Settings' menu item 'Save'"
@toc FM_S

'Settings' menu item 'Save'
---------------------------

This menu item saves the configuration.

The  configuration  file,  'Reflex.cfg' will be saved to 'PROGDIR:'. If you
prefer  it in 'MAIL:' you are welcome to copy it thereto. When Reflex fails
to  read  the configuration file from 'PROGDIR:' it will attempt to read it
from  'MAIL:'.  Is the configuration file read from 'MAIL:' it will also be
saved to 'MAIL:'.

Changes  made in the configuration windows will not be saved until you have
selected this menu item.

The  ARexx  command  corresponding to this menu item is named @{b}SAVESETTINGS@{ub}.
See also @{b}ISCFGCHANGED@{ub}. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_A "The 'ARexx' menu"
@toc FLEXGUI

The 'ARexx' menu
-----------------

The  'ARexx'  menu  contains  ways  of  executing ARexx scripts from within
Reflex. The menu contains the following menu items:

   @{" Execute script... " LINK FM_AES}
   --------------------
   @{" >> user <<        " LINK FM_AS}
   @{" >> user <<        " LINK FM_AS}

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_AES "'ARexx' menu item 'Execute script...'"
@toc FM_A

'ARexx' menu item 'Execute script...'
-------------------------------------

Selecting  this  menu item will prompt you with a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS} filerequester
for  selecting  an  ARexx  script.  The  filerequester  will  open  in  the
@{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}  and  display scripts with the suffix '.flex'. All ARexx
scripts for Reflex ought to end with the suffix '.flex'.

If you select an ARexx script Reflex will execute it asynchronously.

Execution of ARexx scripts is only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FM_AS "'ARexx' menu item '>> user <<'"
@toc FM_A

'ARexx' menu item '>> user <<'
------------------------------

The  @{" ARexx menu " LINK FM_A}  can  contain  up  to  40 by the user pre-selected ARexx
scripts.  This selection is performed in the @{" ARexx configuration " LINK CFGR} window.
All ARexx scripts for Reflex ought to end with the suffix '.flex'.

If you select one of the user selected ARexx scripts Reflex will attempt to
execute it.

Execution of ARexx scripts is only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/Files help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CFGF "Files configuration window"
@toc FLEXGUI

Files configuration window
--------------------------

In  the  Files  configuration  window  you  set some pathnames and a single
filename. The Files configuration window looks a bit like:

   ----------- Paths ------------
   Outbound @{"                  " LINK CFGF_PO }@{"D" LINK CFGF_REQD}
   Nodelist @{"                  " LINK CFGF_PN }@{"D" LINK CFGF_REQD}
   Attach   @{"                  " LINK CFGF_PAD}@{"D" LINK CFGF_REQD}
   ARexx    @{"                  " LINK CFGF_AD }@{"D" LINK CFGF_REQD}
   ------------ File ------------
   Log file @{"                  " LINK CFGF_LF }@{"F" LINK CFGF_REQF}
   ------------------------------
   @{"      Ok      " LINK CFGF_OK}@{"    Cancel    " LINK CFGF_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  in  one  or more of the gadgets and leave the
configuration  window  via  the @{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CFGF_OK} the changed settings are not
saved.  They  will not be saved until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in
the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The  Files  configuration window can be open from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S} or
using the ARexx command @{b}EDITFILES@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_PO "Files configuration 'Outbound'"
@toc CFGF

Files configuration 'Outbound'
------------------------------

In  the  'Outbound'  string  gadget you enter the full path to the outbound
directory.  It  will  have been configured at the initial startup of Reflex
and will probably not have to be re-configured.

The  gadget  to  the  right  of  the  string gadget will open a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS}
directory requester for you to select the outbound directory.

The  ARexx  command  @{b}GETOUTBOUND@{ub}  can  be  used  to  obtain the name of the
outbound directory. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_PN "Files configuration 'Nodelist'"
@toc CFGF

Files configuration 'Nodelist'
------------------------------

In  the  'Nodelist'  string  gadget you enter the full path to the nodelist
directory.  The  nodelist  directory  contains  the nodelists compiled with
@{" TrapList " LINK TRAPLIST} - @{" traplist.library " LINK TRAPLIST} is required for using the nodelists.

You  will  probably  have configured this already at the initial startup of
Reflex.

If  you  don't  enter  a nodelist directory Reflex will not try to open the
nodelists.

The  gadget  to  the  right  of  the  string gadget will open a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS}
directory requester for you to select the nodelist directory.

The  ARexx  command  @{b}GETNODELIST@{ub}  can  be  used  to  obtain the name of the
nodelist directory. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_PAD "Files configuration 'Attach'"
@toc CFGF

Files configuration 'Attach'
----------------------------

In  the  'Attach'  string  gadget  you  enter  the  full path to the attach
directory.  The  @{" Attach requester " LINK AT}  will  open  its  filerequester in the
attach  directory. You will probably prefer that Reflex defaults the attach
filerequester  in  e.g.  your files directory instead of in Reflex' current
directory.

If  you  don't  enter  an  attach  directory  Reflex  will  open the attach
filerequester in Reflex' current directory.

The  gadget  to  the  right  of  the  string gadget will open a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS}
directory requester for you to select the attach directory.

The ARexx command @{b}GETATTACHDIR@{ub} can be used to obtain the name of the attach
directory. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_AD "Files configuration 'ARexx'"
@toc CFGF

Files configuration 'ARexx'
---------------------------

In  the  'ARexx'  string  gadget  you  enter  the  full  path  to the ARexx
directory. The ARexx directory is the directory in which Reflex will search
for  @{" '_<gadget>.flex' scripts " LINK _AREXX}.   Reflex   will   also   open  its  ARexx
filerequesters  in  this  directory,  e.g.  when  you  select the menu item
@{" Execute script... " LINK FM_AES}.

If  you  don't enter an ARexx directory you will not be able to utilize the
@{" '_<gadget>.flex' scripts " LINK _AREXX}  feature  of Reflex. In addition to this Reflex
will open its ARexx filerequesters in the current directory.

The  gadget  to  the  right  of  the  string gadget will open a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS}
directory requester for you to select the ARexx directory.

The  ARexx  command @{b}GETAREXXDIR@{ub} can be used to obtain the name of the ARexx
directory. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx  commands  and '_<gadget>.flex'  scripts  are  only  available to the
@{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_REQD "ReqTools directory requester"
@toc CFGF

ReqTools directory requester
----------------------------

Selecting  this  gadget will open a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS} directory requester for you
to select the directory.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_LF "Files configuration 'Log file'"
@toc CFGF

Files configuration 'Log file'
------------------------------

In  the  'Log file'  string  gadget  you  enter the full path including the
filename of the file to which Reflex should write its log.

You  will  probably  have configured this already at the initial startup of
Reflex.

If you don't enter a filename for the log file Reflex will not write a log.

The  gadget  to  the  right  of  the  string gadget will open a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS}
filerequester for you to select the filename of the log file.

The  ARexx  command  @{b}GETLOGFILE@{ub}  can  be used to obtain the name of the log
file. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_REQF "ReqTools filerequester"
@toc CFGF

ReqTools filerequester
----------------------

Selecting  this  gadget  will  open  a @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS} filerequester for you to
select the filename.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_OK "Files configuration 'Ok' gadget"
@toc CFGF

Files configuration 'Ok' gadget
-------------------------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used but are not saved. To save the changes select the
@{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGF_CC "Files configuration 'Cancel' gadget"
@toc CFGF

Files configuration 'Cancel' gadget
-----------------------------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/GUI help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CGUI "GUI configuration window"
@toc FLEXGUI

GUI configuration window
------------------------

In  the  GUI  configuration  window you set a couple of settings concerning
@{" QuickHelp " LINK QUICKHELP},  progress requesters and other settings concerning the GUI of
Reflex. The GUI configuration window looks a bit like:

   ----------- QuickHelp ------------
   @{"  " LINK CGUI_QH } Main window QuickHelp
   @{"  " LINK CGUI_CQH} Configuration window QuickHelp
   ----------------------------------
   @{"  " LINK CGUI_S  } Progress requesters
   ------------ Listview ------------
   Minimum height of listview @{"    " LINK CGUI_MH}@{"I" LINK CGUI_GMH}
   ----------- Background -----------
   Background    @{"G|                 " LINK CGUI_BG }
   ------------- Screen -------------
   Public screen @{"                   " LINK CGUI_PS }
   ----------------------------------
   @{"       Ok       " LINK CGUI_OK}@{"     Cancel     " LINK CGUI_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CGUI_OK}  the changed settings are not saved. They will not be saved
until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The  GUI  configuration  window can be open from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S} or
using the ARexx command @{b}EDITGUI@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_QH "GUI configuration 'Main window QuickHelp'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Main window QuickHelp'
-----------------------------------------

If  you  tick  this  checkbox  @{" QuickHelp " LINK QUICKHELP}  will  be  enabled  for Reflex'
@{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI}.  After  a  while  most  probably  will  find  the QuickHelp
annoying for the main window.

Requesters uses the main window QuickHelp setting too.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_CQH "GUI configuration 'Configuration window QuickHelp'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Configuration window QuickHelp'
--------------------------------------------------

If   you   tick   this  checkbox  @{" QuickHelp " LINK QUICKHELP}  will  be  enabled  for  the
configuration   windows.   While   QuickHelp  might  be  annoying  for  the
@{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI} after a while some might still like it for the configuration
windows.

Requesters uses the @{" main window QuickHelp " LINK CGUI_QH} setting.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_S "GUI configuration 'Progress requesters'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Progress requesters'
---------------------------------------

When  this  checkbox is ticked Reflex will display progress requesters when
performing  a @{" rescan " LINK F_R} or a @{" maintenance " LINK F_M}. When the checkbox isn't ticked
the progress requesters are suppressed.

User  progress  requesters  displayed  by  the user using the ARexx command
@{b}OPENPROGRESS@{ub}  are not suppressed if the checkbox isn't ticked. Please refer
to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more information about this ARexx command
and   the   other  two  progress  requester  commands,  @{b}UPDATEPROGRESS@{ub}  and
@{b}CLOSEPROGRESS@{ub}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_MH "GUI configuration 'Minimum height of listview'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Minimum height of listview'
----------------------------------------------

Reflex opens the @{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI} with a default listview height of 10 lines.
This  height  of  the listview can be increased - or lowered - to suit your
wishes. If your screen height can accomodate for example 25 lines you might
prefer  this  because  it  gives  you a better overview of the files in the
outbound directory.

In  the  directory  'ENV:Triton'  @{" Triton " LINK TRITON}  stores  information  about the
@{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI}.  Unfortunately  it also stores the height of the window, so
if  you  lower  the height value of the listview Triton might open the main
window  with  the old height value. Therefore it can be necessary to delete
the  file  'Reflex.win.1'  in  'ENV:Triton' before opening the main window.
Please  notice  this  also  applies if you quit Reflex and restart it - the
file  'Reflex.win.1'  still  exists  in  'ENV:Triton'  and might have to be
deleted  before  Reflex  is  able to open with a new and lower value of the
listview  height. Unless you copy 'Reflex.win.1' to 'ENVARC:Triton' you can
always reboot the computer.

Unfortunately  @{" Triton " LINK TRITON}  still  doesn't  offer an integer gadget. Until it
does  the  string  gadget  will  be  disabled and until then new values are
entered  through  a  @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS}  integer  requester  which  is  invoked by
clicking  the  small  entry  button to the right of the string gadget. Tell
@{" Stefan " LINK TRITON} that you want an integer gadget too.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_GMH "GUI configuration 'Minimum height of listview' requester"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Minimum height of listview' requester
--------------------------------------------------------

This  is a standard @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS} integer requester. When @{" Triton " LINK TRITON} offers an
integer gadget this requester will be removed.

Enter the @{" minimum height of the listview " LINK CGUI_MH} in the requester.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_BG "GUI configuration 'Background'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Background'
------------------------------

@{" Triton " LINK TRITON} offers various backgrounds for its windows and requesters. I have
chosen  a - talking standard Workbench colours - a light blue background as
the default background for Reflex' windows and requesters.

Use the cycle gadget to choose background:


@{b}Reflex@{ub}

The @{b}Reflex@{ub} background. The default light blue background.


@{b}Triton@{ub}

The  @{b}Triton@{ub}  background.  Being  a registered @{" Triton " LINK TRITON} user you can choose
backgrounds  for  the  windows  and requesters of Reflex through the Triton
preferences system amongst all the different backgrounds Triton offer.

This  background  type  will  default  to  @{b}None@{ub} if you are not a registered
Triton user.


@{b}None@{ub}

No  background.  This  is probably a standard Amiga background. Just boring
grey  -  just  like  the  background in Spot's windows and requesters. Some
prefer it this way.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_PS "GUI configuration 'Public screen'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Public screen'
---------------------------------

In  this  gadget  you  enter  the name of the public screen on which Reflex
shall open its windows and requesters.

If  you  don't  enter  a public screen name or the public screen isn't open
Reflex  will  open  its windows and requesters on the default public screen
(normally this is the Workbench screen).

The ARexx command @{b}GETPUBSCREEN@{ub} can be used to obtain the name of the public
screen. Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_OK "GUI configuration 'Ok'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Ok'
----------------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used but are not saved. To save the changes select the
@{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

Have you made changes Reflex will close its @{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI} and reopen it to
update the user interface settings.

[À]
@endnode

@node CGUI_CC "GUI configuration 'Cancel'"
@toc CGUI

GUI configuration 'Cancel'
--------------------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/General help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CFGG "General configuration window"
@toc FLEXGUI

General configuration window
----------------------------

In the General configuration window you set a couple of settings concerning
hotkeys,  rescanning and more. The General configuration window looks a bit
like:

   -------------- Hotkeys ---------------
   Popup  @{"                              " LINK CFGG_HP}
   Rescan @{"                              " LINK CFGG_HR}
   Quit   @{"                              " LINK CFGG_HQ}
   ------------- Rescanning -------------
   @{"  " LINK CFGG_PSC} Rescan at popup
   ------------ Miscellaneous -----------
   Popup @{"  " LINK CFGG_POP}  Priority @{"               " LINK CFGG_PRI}@{"I" LINK CFGG_GPRI}
   --------------------------------------
   @{"        Ok        " LINK CFGG_OK}@{"      Cancel      " LINK CFGG_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CFGG_OK}  the changed settings are not saved. They will not be saved
until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The  General  configuration window can be open from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}
or using the ARexx command @{b}EDITGENERAL@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_HP "General configuration 'Popup' hotkey"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Popup' hotkey
------------------------------------

In  this string gadget you enter the @{" hotkey " LINK HOTKEYS} for making Reflex pop up its
graphic user interface, i.e. the @{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI}.

The string gadget can of course be left empty.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_HR "General configuration 'Rescan' hotkey"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Rescan' hotkey
-------------------------------------

In  this string gadget you enter the @{" hotkey " LINK HOTKEYS} for making Reflex rescan the
outbound directory.

The string gadget can of course be left empty.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_HQ "General configuration 'Quit' hotkey"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Quit' hotkey
-----------------------------------

In this string gadget you enter the @{" hotkey " LINK HOTKEYS} for quitting Reflex.

The string gadget can of course be left empty.

[À]
@endnode

@node HOTKEYS "Hotkeys"

Hotkeys
-------

Hotkeys  are an input description strings. The following regular expression
outlines the format of the input event description string:

    { [-] (qualifier | synonym) }  [ [-] upstroke ]  [ highmap | ANSICode ]

Such input description strings are filtered through Commodities.

@{i}Qualifier@{ui}  is  one  of  the  qualifier strings from the table below. A dash
preceding  the qualifier string tells the Commodities filter not to care if
that qualifier is present in the input event. Notice that there can be more
than one qualifier (or none at all) in the input description string.

   @{b}Qualifier String@{ub}    @{b}Key@{ub}

   "lshift"            left shift key
   "rshift"            right shift key
   "capslock"          caps lock
   "control"           control key
   "lalt"              left alt
   "ralt"              right alt
   "lcommand"          left Amiga key
   "rcommand"          right Amiga key
   "numericpad"        numeric keypad key

@{i}Synonym@{ui}  is  one of the synonym strings from the table below. These strings
act  as  synonyms  for  groups  of qualifiers. A dash preceding the synonym
string  tells the Commodities filter not to care if that synonym is present
in the input event. Notice that there can be more than one synonym (or none
at all) in the input description string.

   @{b}Synonym String@{ub}      @{b}Key@{ub}

   "shift"             either shift key
   "caps"              either shift key or caps lock
   "alt"               either alt key

@{i}Upstroke@{ui}  is  the  literal string "upstroke". If this string is absent, the
filter  considers  only  downstrokes.  It  it  is present alone, the filter
considers  only upstrokes. If preceded by a dash, the filter considers both
upstrokes and downstrokes.

@{i}Highmap@{ui} is one of the following strings:

   "space", "backspace", "tab", "enter", "return", "esc", "del", "up",
   "down", "right", "left", "f1", "f2", "f3", "f4", "f5", "f6", "f7",
   "f8", "f9", "f10", "help".

@{i}ANSICode@{ui}  is a single character (for example 'a') that Commodities Exchange
looks up in the system default keymap.

The Reflex default rescan hotkey is:

   "lcommand rcommand r"

meaning  that  when you press left Amiga key, right Amiga key, and 'r' then
Reflex will rescan.


This section is more or less a transcript from Commodore-Amiga, Inc.: @{i}AMIGA
ROM  Kernel  Reference Manual: Libraries@{ui}, 3rd Edition: Commodities Exchange
Library, Filter Objects and Input Description Strings, p. 736-737.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_POP "General configuration 'Popup'"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Popup'
-----------------------------

If  you  tick  this checkbox Reflex will open its graphic user interface at
startup. Otherwise Reflex will run silently in the background.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_PRI "General configuration 'Priority'"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Priority'
--------------------------------

This is the priority of the Reflex Commodities broker.

Unfortunately  @{" Triton " LINK TRITON}  still  doesn't  offer an integer gadget. Until it
does  the  string  gadget  will  be  disabled and until then new values are
entered  through  a  @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS}  integer  requester  which  is  invoked by
clicking  the  small  entry  button to the right of the string gadget. Tell
@{" Stefan " LINK TRITON} that you want an integer gadget too.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_GPRI "General configuration 'Priority' requester"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Priority' requester
------------------------------------------

This  is a standard @{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS} integer requester. When @{" Triton " LINK TRITON} offers an
integer gadget this requester will be removed.

Enter the @{" priority " LINK CFGG_PRI} of the Reflex Commodities broker in the requester.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_PSC "General configuration 'Rescan at popup'"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Rescan at popup'
---------------------------------------

If  you  tick this checkbox Reflex will rescan the outbound directory prior
to popping up the @{" main window " LINK FLEXGUI} when using the @{" popup hotkey " LINK CFGG_HP}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_OK "General configuration 'Ok'"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Ok'
--------------------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used but are not saved. To save the changes select the
@{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

The priority of the Reflex Commodities broker is not used until you restart
Reflex.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGG_CC "General configuration 'Cancel'"
@toc CFGG

General configuration 'Cancel'
------------------------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/Nodebook help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CFGN "Nodebook window"
@toc FLEXGUI

Nodebook window
---------------

From  the  Nodebook window you are able to set special settings for certain
nodes.  The Nodebook is a kind of telephone book clone. The Nodebook window
looks a bit like:

   ------- Nodebook ---------
   Nodes @{"                   " LINK CFGN_L}

         @{"  Add   " LINK CFGN_A}@{"  Delete  " LINK CFGN_D}
         @{"       Edit        " LINK CFGN_E}
         @{"   Up   " LINK CFGN_U}@{"   Down   " LINK CFGN_O}
         @{"       Sort        " LINK CFGN_S}
         @{"       Poll        " LINK CFGN_C}
   --------------------------
   @{"     Ok     " LINK CFGN_OK}@{"   Cancel   " LINK CFGN_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CFGN_OK}  the changed settings are not saved. They will not be saved
until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The Nodebook window can be opened from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S} or using the
ARexx command @{b}EDITNODEBOOK@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

The ARexx command @{b}NB_GETNUMNODES@{ub} can be used to obtain the number of nodes
in the Nodebook.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_L "Nodebook listview"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook listview
-----------------

The  Nodebook listview contains the addresses of the nodes currently in the
Nodebook.

The  ARexx command @{b}NB_GETNUMNODES@{ub} can be used to obtain the number of nodes
in  the  Nodebook.  The command @{b}NB_ISNODE@{ub} can be used to check if a certain
node  is  listed  in  the Nodebook. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more
information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_A "Nodebook 'Add'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Add'
--------------

Selecting  the  'Add'  button will invoke the @{" Nodebook Editor " LINK NE} for you to
add a new node to the Nodebook.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_D "Nodebook 'Delete'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Delete'
-----------------

Selecting  the  'Delete'  button  will  remove  the  current  node from the
Nodebook.  Reflex will prompt you with a requester before actually removing
the node.

The 'Delete' button will be disabled if the listview is empty.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_E "Nodebook 'Edit'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Edit'
---------------

Selecting  the  'Edit'  button  will  invoke the @{" Nodebook Editor " LINK NE} for the
current  node.  If  you  want to change the settings for a certain node you
will select the 'Edit' button.

The  Nodebook  Editor  for the current node can be invoke too if you either
double click the node in the listview or press the return key.

The 'Edit' button will be disabled if the listview i empty.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_U "Nodebook 'Up'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Up'
-------------

The  'Up'  button  will move the current node one entry up in the listview.
Please  notice, that the @{" Node requester " LINK RN} will be sorted in the same order
as  the  Nodebook - therefore the order of the nodes might be of importance
to you

The  'Up'  button  will be disabled if the listview is empty or the current
entry is the first entry in the listview.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_O "Nodebook 'Down'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Down'
---------------

The  'Down'  button  will  move  the  current  node  one  entry down in the
listview.  Please  notice, that the @{" Node requester " LINK RN} will be sorted in the
same  order  as the Nodebook - therefore the order of the nodes might be of
importance to you

The  'Down' button will be disabled if the listview is empty or the current
entry is the last entry in the listview.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_S "Nodebook 'Sort'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Sort'
---------------

Selecting  the  'Sort'  button  will  sort  the  nodes  according  to their
addresses. The sort function requires the @{" traplist.library " LINK TRAPLIST}.

Please notice, that the @{" Node requester " LINK RN} will be sorted in the same order
as  the  Nodebook - therefore the order of the nodes might be of importance
to you

The 'Sort' button will be disabled if the listview is empty or only contain
one  entry.  It  will  naturally  be disabled too if traplist.library isn't
available.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_C "Nodebook 'Poll'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Poll'
---------------

Selecting  the  'Poll'  button  will instruct Reflex to attempt to call the
current node in the listview.

Please  notice, that if you have made changes Reflex will use these for the
call.  These changed settings will only be available at a later time if you
leave the Nodebook using the @{" Ok " LINK CFGN_OK} button.

The 'Poll' button will be disabled if the listview is empty. If there isn't
specified  a  @{" Poll command " LINK CFGM_PC}  in  the  @{" Mailer configuration " LINK CFGM}  it will be
disabled too.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_OK "Nodebook 'Ok'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Ok'
-------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used but are not saved. To save the changes select the
@{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGN_CC "Nodebook 'Cancel'"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook 'Cancel'
-----------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

All  changes  made  both  in the Nodebook window and in the Nodebook Editor
will be discarded.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/Nodebook Editor help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node NE "Nodebook Editor"
@toc CFGN

Nodebook Editor
---------------

In  the  Nodebook  Editor you enter the actual settings for a certain node.
The Nodebook Editor looks a bit like:

   -------------- Nodebook --------------
   Node     @{"                            " LINK NE_N }
   System   @{"                            " LINK NE_SYSTEM}
   Sysop    @{"                            " LINK NE_SYSOP}
   ------------- Operation --------------
   Poll     @{"                            " LINK NE_C}
   Phone    @{"                            " LINK NE_PH}
   Port     @{"                            " LINK NE_PO}
   Options  @{"                            " LINK NE_MO}
   ----------- Miscellaneous ------------
   @{"  " LINK NE_NC} Prevent calls  @{"  " LINK NE_NR} Node requester
   -------------- TrapList --------------
   Password @{"                            " LINK NE_PWD}
   --------------------------------------
   @{"        Ok        " LINK NE_OK}@{"      Cancel      " LINK NE_CC}
	
If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave  the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CFGM_OK}  the  changed  settings  are not saved. The changed settings
will  be  used  when  you  return  to the @{" Nodebook " LINK CFGN} and will be discarded
unless  you  also  selects  'Ok'  from  within  the Nodebook. They will not
actually   be  saved  until  you  select  the  @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}  in  the
@{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The  ARexx command @{b}NB_GETNUMNODES@{ub} can be used to obtain the number of nodes
in the Nodebook.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_N "Nodebook Editor 'Node'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Node'
----------------------

In  the  'Node'  string  gadget  of  the Nodebook Editor you enter the Fido
address  of the node you want to put in the Nodebook. This naturally has to
be a valid Fido address.

Reflex  will  automatically  fill the @{i}System@{ui} and @{i}Sysop@{ui} fields beneath if a
nodelist is available.

You  can  use  the @{b}NB_ISNODE@{ub} to check if a certain node is in the Nodebook.
See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_SYSTEM "Nodebook Editor 'System'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'System'
------------------------

This  field  is  automatically filled with the system name when you enter a
new Fido address if the address is found in the available nodelists.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_SYSOP "Nodebook Editor 'Sysop'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Sysop'
-----------------------

This field is automatically filled with the sysop name when you enter a new
Fido address if the address is found in the available nodelists.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_C "Nodebook Editor 'Poll'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Poll'
----------------------

In  this  string  gadget  you  can  enter  a valid Fido address. This is an
alternative  address  Reflex  will  use instead of the one specified in the
@{" Node " LINK NE_N} string gadget above.

@{i}Alternative@{ui}  is  probably  not  the best term to use, since this address is
used  instead  of  the  actual address. That is - if mail is destined for a
node  Reflex  will  use  this  address  instead  of the actual address when
attempting to call the other system.

Let  me  give  an  example.  Let's  pretend  that  I have got an ISDN line.
Therefore  I  would  naturally prefer to call my boss' ISDN line instead of
his  normal  phone line. So when I've got mail destined for 2:238/127 in my
outbound directory I want Reflex to call 2:238/1006 instead. Therefore I've
got a Nodebook entry for 2:238/127 with the 'Poll' string 2:238/1006.

In  the  above  case I would probably also put something like 'TrapISDN' in
the @{" Port " LINK NE_PO} string gadget of the Nodebook Editor.

Normally  Reflex  will  substitute the @{" Poll command's " LINK CFGM_PC} %n formatting code
with the node number. If a alternative address is specified in the Nodebook
for the node in question this alternative address will be used instead.

You  can  use  the  ARexx  command @{b}NB_POLL@{ub} to obtain a possible alternative
address  for  a  certain  node.  See  the  @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}  for more
information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_PH "Nodebook Editor 'Phone'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Phone'
-----------------------

In  this string gadget you can enter a phone number. This works in the same
way  as the @{" Poll " LINK NE_C} string above this gadget. I.e. if a telephone number is
specified  for  a node Reflex will use this instead of the node number when
substituting the %n formatting code in the @{" Poll command " LINK CFGM_PC}.

This  is especially usefull if you want to call points. Points are normally
not listed in nodelists.

You  can  use  the  ARexx command @{b}NB_PHONE@{ub} to obtain a possible alternative
phone number  for  a  certain node. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more
information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_PO "Nodebook Editor 'Port'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Port'
----------------------

The  'Port'  string gadget is used to specify a portname different from the
@{" Default portname " LINK CFGM_PON}.

The  portname  is  placed  instead  of  the  %p formatting code when Reflex
executes the @{" Poll command " LINK CFGM_PC}.

If  you're  only  running a single node system you do not have to specify a
portname  -  nor  a default portname - since you will probably not be using
the %p formatting code. If you have specified the %p formatting code in the
poll command string you @{i}must@{ui} at least specify a default portname.

Specifying  an  alternative  portname can be used to address a mailer other
than  the  default  one. This is for example use full if you've got an ISDN
line  and  want  to  address the ISDN-mailer for certain nodes. Putting the
portname of the ISDN-mailer in the 'Port' gadget will enable you to address
the correct mailer.

You  can  use  the  ARexx  command @{b}NB_PORT@{ub} to obtain a possible alternative
portname  for  a  certain  node.  See  the  @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more
information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_MO "Nodebook Editor 'Options'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Options'
-------------------------

In the 'Options' string gadget you can put miscellaneous options to send to
the  mailer  for  a  certain  node. These options are put instead of the %m
formatting code in the @{" Poll command " LINK CFGM_PC}.

With some systems I'm unable to get a handshake with 14400 connect but with
a 9600 connect everything works fine. Therefore I have a

   BAUD 9600

option for certain nodes ensuring a correct session handshake.

At  least  @{" TrapDoor " LINK TRAPDOOR}  remembers  such  settings as the one above from one
session  to the next. Please remember this before using %m, because a 'BAUD
2400' might result in 2400 baud connects until you restart TrapDoor.

You  can  use the ARexx command @{b}NB_OPTIONS@{ub} to obtain possible options for a
certain node. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_NC "Nodebook Editor 'Prevent calls'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Prevent calls'
-------------------------------

If  you  tick  this  checkbox  Reflex will prevent calls to the system even
though the address matches the @{" Poll pattern " LINK CFGM_PAT}.

Please  notice, that the check is made before Reflex substitute the address
with and alternative address from the Nodebook.

You can use the ARexx command @{b}NB_PREVENTCALL@{ub} to check if calls to a certain
node are allowed. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_NR "Nodebook Editor 'Node requester'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Node requester'
--------------------------------

Ticking  this checkbox will instruct Reflex to place the system in question
in the @{" Node requester " LINK RN}. This will give you easy access to the systems you
use most frequently.

You  can  use  the  ARexx command @{b}NB_NODEREQ@{ub} to check if calls to a certain
node  are  allowed.  This  ARexx  command  is  probably  useless.  See  the
@{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more information.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_PWD "Nodebook Editor 'Password'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Password'
--------------------------

The  @{i}Password@{ui}  string  gadget  is  only enabled when @{" traplist.library " LINK TRAPLIST} is
available.

This  string  gadget  is a GUI interface to the session passwords. It works
exactly  like  the  SetPasswd  shell  command  that  comes  along  with the 
@{" TrapDoor " LINK TRAPDOOR} distribution.

The  session  password is not stored by Reflex. traplist.library is capable
of doing this by itself.

To  obtain  a  session password in an ARexx script you will have to use the
ARexx interface of traplist.library.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_OK "Nodebook Editor 'Ok'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Ok'
--------------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used from within the @{" Nodebook configuration " LINK CFGN} window.
The  changes  will  be  discarded  if you select the 'Cancel' gadget in the
Nodebook configuration window.

Therefore,  to save the changes select 'Ok' in the Nodebook Editor, 'Ok' in
the  Nodebook  configuration  window  and select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} to
actually save the changes to the configuration file.

Please  notice  that  if you select 'Ok' in the Nodebook Editor the session
password  @{i}will@{ui}  be  changed regardless of you choice of 'Ok' or 'Cancel' in
the Nodebook configuration window.

[À]
@endnode

@node NE_CC "Nodebook Editor 'Cancel'"
@toc NE

Nodebook Editor 'Cancel'
------------------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/Deletion help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node DCFG "Deletion configuration window"
@toc FLEXGUI

Deletion configuration window
-----------------------------

In  the  Deletion  configuration  window  you  decide which files Reflex is
allowed   to  delete  when  it  performs  a  @{" maintenance " LINK F_M}.  The  Deletion
configuration window looks a bit like:

   ----- Outbound file deletion -----
   @{"  " LINK DCFG_O} Delete orphan files
   @{"  " LINK DCFG_E} Delete empty files
   @{"  " LINK DCFG_M} Delete missing file entries
   ----------------------------------
   Delete at @{"G|                     " LINK DCFG_W}
   ----------------------------------
   @{"       Ok       " LINK DCFG_OK}@{"     Cancel     " LINK DCFG_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK DCFG_OK}  the changed settings are not saved. They will not be saved
until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The  Deletion configuration window can be open from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}
or using the ARexx command @{b}EDITDELETION@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node DCFG_E "Deletion configuration 'Delete empty files'"
@toc DCFG

Deletion configuration 'Delete empty files'
-------------------------------------------

When  this checkbox is ticked Reflex is allowed to delete @{" empty files " LINK ENTRYTYPES} in
the outbound directory when performing a maintenance.

[À]
@endnode

@node DCFG_O "Deletion configuration 'Delete orphan files'
@toc DCFG

Deletion configuration 'Delete orphan files'
--------------------------------------------

When this checkbox is ticked Reflex is allowed to delete @{" orphan files " LINK ENTRYTYPES} in
the outbound directory when performing a maintenance.

[À]
@endnode

@node DCFG_M "Deletion configuration 'Delete missing file entries'"
@toc DCFG

Deletion configuration 'Delete missing file entries'
----------------------------------------------------

When  this checkbox is ticked Reflex is allowed to delete flow file entries
of @{" missing files " LINK ENTRYTYPES} when performing a maintenance.

[À]
@endnode

@node DCFG_W "Deletion configuration 'Delete at'"
@toc DCFG

Deletion configuration 'Delete at'
----------------------------------

You use this cycle gadget to decide when to perform maintenance.

@{b}Maintenance only@{ub}  will  only  perform  a  maintenance  when  you select the
@{" 'Maintenance' " LINK F_M} or execute the ARexx command @{b}MAINTENANCE@{ub}.

@{b}Rescan/Maintenance@{ub} will also perform a maintenance right after a rescan has
been completed.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node DCFG_OK "Deletion configuration 'Ok'"
@toc DCFG

Deletion configuration 'Ok'
---------------------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used but are not saved. To save the changes select the
@{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

[À]
@endnode

@node DCFG_CC "Deletion configuration 'Cancel'"
@toc DCFG

Deletion configuration 'Cancel'
-------------------------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

[À]
@endnode

@remark ----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Attach requester
@remark ----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node AT "Attach requester"
@toc FLEXGUI

Attach requester
----------------

In  the  Attach requester you select the files to attach to another system.
The Attach requester looks a bit like:

   ------------------------ Attach file ------------------------
   ------ Receiving system ----- | ---------- File(s) ----------
   Node    @{"                  " LINK AT_N}@{"N" LINK AT_GN} |
   System  @{"                    " LINK AT_SYSTEM} |
   Sysop   @{"                    " LINK AT_SYSOP} | @{"                             " LINK AT_L}
   --------- Attributes -------- |
   Status  @{"G|                  " LINK AT_S} |
   Action  @{"G|                  " LINK AT_A} |
   ------- Miscellaneous ------- | @{"                             " LINK AT_F}
   @{"  " LINK AT_CO} Copy file to outbound     | @{"     Add      " LINK AT_GF}@{"    Delete    " LINK AT_D}
   @{"  " LINK AT_AD} Attach description        | @{"            Edit             " LINK AT_E}
   --------------------------------------------------------------
   @{"              Ok              " LINK AT_OK}@{"            Cancel            " LINK AT_CC}

You  use  the Attach requester to attach files to other systems. You simply
choose the address of the system to which you will be attaching files; then
you  select  the  files to attach; and finally 'Ok' to actually perform the
attaching.

You  must  leave  the  requester  via  the  @{" 'Ok' button " LINK AT_OK} for the files to
actually  be  attached. To cancel the attaching of the files just click the
@{" 'Cancel' button " LINK AT_CC}.

The Attach requester will open with the address of the current entry in the
listview - that is naturally if the current entry has a valid Fido address.

If you prefer the Attach requester to open with an empty node string gadget
you  can  use an '_Attach.flex' ARexx script that will be executed when you
select  the  'Attach'  button  in  the main listview. In the '_Attach.flex'
script  you  will  use the REQUESTATTACH ARexx command to invoke the Attach
requester.  Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more information
about using ARexx.

Attributes for the files to attach can be different for each file to attach.
You  change  the  attributes  @{i}before@{ui}  you  select the file(s) to have those
attributes.  The  attributes  will be displayed to the left of the files in
the listview

When  you  open  the  Attach  requester  the attributes will be as you have
chosen in the @{" Attaching " LINK CFGA} configuration window.

The  Attach requester is either opened from the 'Attach' button in the main
window or by using the REQUESTATTACH ARexx command.

ARexx commands and scripts are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_N "Attach requester 'Node'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Node'
-----------------------

In  the  'Node'  string gadget you enter the Fido address of the system for
which you want to attach files.

If  you  opened  the Attach requester using the 'Attach' button in the main
window  this  string  gadget will be filled with the address of the current
entry in the listview if the entry has a valid Fido address.

Is  Reflex  able  to  find  the  system in the nodelist it will fill in the
System and Sysop field in the requester.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_SYSTEM "Attach requester 'System'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'System'
-------------------------

This  field will hold the system name of the system specified in the 'Node'
gadget above.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_SYSOP "Attach requester 'Sysop'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Sysop'
------------------------

This  field  will hold the sysop name of the system specified in the 'Node'
gadget above.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_GN "Attach requester 'Node requester'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Node requester'
---------------------------------

Selecting this gadget will invoke the @{" Node requester " LINK NR} for you to select a
node among those selected within the Nodebook.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_F "Attach requester 'File'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'File'
-----------------------

In  this  string  gadget  you can enter the filename of the file to attach.
Please  notice,  that you will have to enter the filename respective to the
current directory or with a full path.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_GF "Attach requester 'Add'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Add'
----------------------

Selecting  the  'Add' gadget will open a multiselect ReqTools filerequester
for you to select the files to attach.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_S "Attach requester 'Status'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Status'
-------------------------

Using the cycle gadget you choose the prefered status; @{i}Normal@{ui}, @{i}Crash@{ui}, @{i}Hold@{ui}
or  @{i}Direct@{ui}  of  the  file(s)  to be attach. The status the Attach requester
opens with can be configured in the @{" Attaching " LINK CFGA} configuration window.

Please  notice,  that  all  attributes only apply to files attach after the
attributes have been changed.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_A "Attach requester 'Action'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Action'
-------------------------

This  cycle gadget is used to set the mailer action of the files to attach.
The  mailer  action  is  either  @{i}No special processing@{ui},  @{i}Truncate to zero@{ui},
@{i}Delete with logging@{ui},   @{i}Delete without logging@{ui},  or  @{i}No special processing,
allow filenote tagging@{ui}. See your mailer documentation for more information
about  these  mailer  actions. The mailer action the Attach requester opens
with can be configured in the @{" Attaching " LINK CFGA} configuration window.

Please  notice,  that  all  attributes only apply to files attach after the
attributes have been changed.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_CO "Attach requester 'Copy file to outbound'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Copy file to outbound'
----------------------------------------

Have  you  ticked this checkbox the following attached files will be copied
to the outbound directory.

If  a  file  with  the  same  name already exists in the outbound directory
Reflex  will  ignore  this  setting  and  attach  the  file  from  its home
directory.

When  the Attach requester opens this checkbox will be configured according
to the settings you have made in the @{" Attaching " LINK CFGA} configuration window.

Please  notice,  that  all  attributes only apply to files attach after the
attributes have been changed.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_AD "Attach requester 'Auto attach description'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Auto attach description'
------------------------------------------

Is  this  checkbox  ticked Reflex will attempt to locate a description file
according  to  the  description  file pattern specified in the @{" Attaching " LINK CFGA}
configuration window. Does Reflex find a match the description file will be
attached along with the file with the same attach attributes.

If  no  description  file  is  found  Reflex  will  then - according to the
settings  in  the  Attaching  configuration window - attach the filenote if
such  exists.  This file will be located in the outbound directory and will
be deleted when it has been sent. (Does there already exist a file with the
same  name  in  the outbound directory the filenote will not be attach as a
description).

When  the Attach requester opens this checkbox will be configured according
to the settings you have made in the @{" Attaching " LINK CFGA} configuration window.

Please  notice,  that  all  attributes only apply to files attach after the
attributes have been changed.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_E "Attach requester 'Edit'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Edit'
-----------------------

Currently  this button will be disabled all the time. This is because I for
some reason never have come around implementing the actions of this button.

It is the intension, that clicking the 'Edit' button would open a small GUI
for you to change the attributes of the current file in the listview of the
Attach requester.

Well,  who  knows.  I  might get around to implementing it sometime. If you
need  it let me know. Until then you will have to select 'Delete' to remove
the  file  from  the  attach list and then re-attach the file if the attach
attributes of the file for some weird reason don't suit you.

If  you  @{" register " LINK REGISTER}  it  might speed up the things a bit - but no promises
though.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_D "Attach requester 'Delete'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Delete'
-------------------------

Clicking  the  'Delete'  gadget  will remove the current file in the attach
list.  Therefore  it will no get attached when you click 'Ok' to attach all
the other files in the attach list.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_L "Attach requester listview"
@toc AT

Attach requester listview
-------------------------

The  listview  displays the list of files to attach to the system specified
in  the  'Node'  string gadget. Please notice, that it is only new attaches
that  are shown in the listview. Files attached earlier either by Reflex or
another program will @{i}not@{ui} be shown in the listview.

The  listview  contains  a  four  character  attribute  description and the
filename. The filename is to the right in the listview and does not include
the full path.

The  attribute description is to the left in the listview and contains four
characters reporting the atttach attributes for the file.

First attribute description character reports the status of the file:

   'N'  -  Normal
   'C'  -  Crash
   'H'  -  Hold
   'D'  -  Direct

Second  attribute  description  character  reports the mailer action of the
file:

   ' '  -  No special processing
   '#'  -  Truncate to zero
   '^'  -  Delete with logging
   '-'  -  Delete without logging
   '@'  -  No special processing, allow filenote tagging

Third attribute description character reports whether or not the file is to
be copied to the outbound directory before it is attached:

   ' '  -  File will @{i}not@{ui} be copied to the outbound directory
   '>'  -  File will be copied to the outbound directory

Fourth  and  last  attribute  description  character reports whether or not
Reflex should attempt to locate a description file to attach along with the
file:

   ' '  -  Description file will @{i}not@{ui} be attached
   '+'  -  Description file will be attached

An example:

   "C^>   file1.lha"

means  that  'file1.lha'  will be attached crash, after it has been sent it
will be deleted with logging. Furthermore 'file1.lha' will be copied to the
outbound directory, and no description file will be attached.

Another example:

   "H  +  file2.lha"

means  that  'file2.lha'  will be attached hold, and Reflex will attempt to
locate  a description file to attach along with the file itself. Second and
third  attribute  description character is ' ' meaning the mailer action is
'no  special  processing'  and  that  the  file  not  will be copied to the
outbound directory.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_OK "Attach requester 'Ok'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Ok'
---------------------

If the attach list contains any files and a valid Fido address is specified
the files will be attach to the system in question when you select the 'Ok'
button.

[À]
@endnode

@node AT_CC "Attach requester 'Cancel'"
@toc AT

Attach requester 'Cancel'
-------------------------

Do you for some reason have second thoughts you can cancel the attaching of
all the files in the attach list by selecting the 'Cancel' button.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/Mailer help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CFGM "Mailer configuration window"
@toc FLEXGUI

Mailer configuration window
---------------------------

In  the  Mailer  configuration window you configure settings concerning the
interaction  with  you  mailer. The Mailer configuration window looks a bit
like:

   ------------- Mailer -------------
   Poll command     @{"                " LINK CFGM_PC }
   Default portname @{"                " LINK CFGM_PON}
   Poll pattern     @{"                " LINK CFGM_PAT}
   ----------------------------------
   @{"       Ok       " LINK CFGM_OK}@{"     Cancel     " LINK CFGM_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CFGM_OK}  the changed settings are not saved. They will not be saved
until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The Mailer configuration window can be open from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S} or
using the ARexx command @{b}EDITMAILER@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGM_PC "Mailer configuration 'Poll command'"
@toc CFGM

Mailer configuration 'Poll command'
-----------------------------------

The  poll command is the command Reflex will execute when you ask Reflex to
call a node. Points will normally use this command to launch the mailer and
nodes will probably use an ARexx script to address the mailer.

At  the  initial  startup  Reflex  will  prompt you with the following poll
command:

   TrapDoor CALL %n

where  %n  is  the  node number. This will start the mailer @{" TrapDoor " LINK TRAPDOOR} and
tell it to call the node in question.

If  TrapDoor is running in answer mode users would probably use @{" TrapTell " LINK TRAPDOOR}
to  tell  the  mailer to call the node in question. If you use TrapTell you
probably  know a lot better than I how to use it. One of my betatesters use
the  following  poll  command  (see  below  for  the  meaning  of the other
formatting codes):

   TrapTell -P%p "CALL %n %m"

If  you  put  an ARexx script in the poll command string gadget you have to
remember  that  Reflex  will  have  to launch the ARexx script by using the
command RX. Therefore you will have to put 'RX' in front of the name of the
ARexx script. One of my betatesters uses the following poll command to tell
the mailer @{" GMS " LINK GMS} to call the node in question:

   RX GMS:rexx/GMS_Tools.rexx POLL=n%

If  you  use  such an ARexx script or even another mailer you ought to know
what to put in the poll command string gadget.

Please  notice,  that other settings might interfere with the result of the
poll  command.  The @{" Poll pattern " LINK CFGM_PAT} and @{" Nodebook " LINK CFGN} setting @{" Prevent call " LINK NE_NC}
might  prevent  Reflex  from  calling  the node in question. Refer to these
sections for more information.

The  poll  command  takes  a  number  of formatting codes. I myself use the
following poll command:

   TrapDoor CALL %n NOQUIET NAME "%r %v - %d" %m

to brag about Reflex.

This is the formatting codes which Reflex understands:

@{b}Node number@{ub} %n

The formatting code %n is probably the most important formatting code. This
formatting  code will insert the node number. Therefore %n is needed in the
poll command string.

If  the  node  in  question has got an entry in the @{" Nodebook " LINK CFGN} Reflex will
look  for  an  @{" alternative node number " LINK NE_C} or an @{" alternative phone number " LINK NE_PH}
and  insert this instead of the node number. Please refer to these sections
for more information.

@{b}Portname@{ub} %p

The formatting code %p will insert the portname. If you are running a multi
node  system  you  might  want  to  address different mailers. This is done
through the portname formatting code.

If  you've  got  two  lines,  say a normal line and an ISDN line, you would
naturally  want  to use the ISDN line if the receiver has got one too. This
can   be  accomplished  by  putting  the  ISDN  line  node  number  in  the
@{" alternative node number " LINK NE_C}  string gadget in the @{" Nodebook Editor " LINK NE} and put
the  name of the ARexx port of the ISDN mailer in the @{" Port " LINK NE_PO} string gadget
in the @{" Nodebook Editor " LINK NE}.

If  you've got a %p formatting code in the poll command and the node hasn't
got an entry in the @{" Nodebook " LINK CFGN} Reflex will use the @{" Default portname " LINK CFGM_PON} and
this  will  therefore  normally be the name of the ARexx port of you mailer
for you normal line.

The following poll command:

   TrapTell -P%p "CALL %n %m"

will address the TrapDoor with the portname %p when Reflex attempts to call
the system %n.

@{b}Misc. options@{ub} %m

The  formatting code %m will insert the @{" Options " LINK NE_MO} for the node in question
from  the @{" Nodebook Editor " LINK NE} if such exists for the node in question. These
options could for example be:

   BAUD 9600

if  you  for some reason has got problem of getting a 14k4 connect with the
system.

At  least  @{" TrapDoor " LINK TRAPDOOR}  remembers  such  settings as the one above from one
session  to the next. Please remember this before using %m, because a 'BAUD
2400' might result in 2400 baud connects until you restart TrapDoor.

@{b}Public screen@{ub} %s

The  formatting code %s will insert the name of the public screen as stated
in the @{" public screen " LINK CGUI_PS} string gadget in the @{" GUI configuration " LINK CGUI} window.

@{b}Useless formatting codes@{ub} %r, %v and %d

The  formatting  codes  %r, %v and %d are a total waste of bytes and nobody
but  myself will probably use them. %r will insert 'Reflex'; %v will insert
the  version  number  of  Reflex;  and  %d  will  insert  a short (probably
localized) description of Reflex. Told you so - they are useless.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGM_PON "Mailer configuration 'Default portname'"
@toc CFGM

Mailer configuration 'Default portname'
---------------------------------------

In  this  string gadget you enter the name of the default ARexx port Reflex
should put instead of the %p formatting code in the @{" Poll command " LINK CFGM_PC}.

Is  another portname specified for the node to call in the @{" Nodebook " LINK CFGN} this
will be put instead of the default portname.

If  the  @{" Poll command " LINK CFGM_PC}  doesn't  include  a  %p formatting code a default
portname is not needed.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGM_PAT "Mailer configuration 'Poll pattern'"
@toc CFGM

Mailer configuration 'Poll pattern'
-----------------------------------

The  poll pattern is a way of filtering the systems to call. Before calling
a system Reflex will pattern match the node number with the poll pattern.

Is  there  a  pattern  match Reflex will attempt to call the system. If the
node number doesn't match the poll pattern the call will not be performed.

The  poll pattern is a node number pattern accepting all AmigaDOS patterns.
The patterns are fairly extensive. Here are the available tokens:

?       Matches a single character.
#       Matches the following expression 0 or more times.
(ab|cd) Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.
~       Negates the following expression.  It matches all strings
        that do not match the expression (aka ~(foo) matches all
        strings that are not exactly "foo").
[abc]   Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
[~bc]   Character class: matches any of the characters not in the
        class.
a-z     Character range (only within character classes).
%       Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").
*       Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.  Available
        as an option that can be turned on.

The default poll pattern is:

   #[0-9]:#[0-9]/#[0-9](%|.#[0-9])

matching all valid 4D node and point addresses.

As another example of a poll pattern is the pattern I use myself:

   (2|39):#[0-9]/#[0-9](%|.#[0-9])

matching all European FidoNet addresses (zone 2) and all European AmigaNet
addresses (zone 39).


Part of this section is a transcript from the DOS autodoc, ParsePattern().

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGM_OK "Mailer configuration 'Ok'"
@toc CFGM

Mailer configuration 'Ok'
-------------------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used but are not saved. To save the changes select the
@{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGM_CC "Mailer configuration 'Cancel'"
@toc CFGM

Mailer configuration 'Cancel'
-----------------------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Status requesters
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CS "Change status requester"
@toc FLEXGUI

Change status requester
-----------------------

This is the Change status requester. This is a simple @{" Status " LINK SR} requester.

It opens with the flavour of the entry of which you want to change status.

[À]
@endnode

@node SR "Status requester" 
@toc FLEXGUI

Status requester
----------------

The  Status  requester  is  used to select a flavour, either @{i}Normal@{ui}, @{i}Crash@{ui},
@{i}Hold@{ui} or @{i}Direct@{ui}. The Status requester looks a bit like:

   -------- Enter status --------
   Status  @{"G|                   " LINK CS_S}
   ------------------------------
   @{"      Ok      " LINK CS_OK}@{"    Cancel    " LINK CS_CC}

The  Status  requester can be opened using the ARexx command @{b}REQUESTSTATUS@{ub}.
See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CS_S "Status requester 'Status'"
@toc SR

Status requester 'Status'
-------------------------

Using the cycle gadget you choose the prefered status; @{i}Normal@{ui}, @{i}Crash@{ui}, @{i}Hold@{ui}
or @{i}Direct@{ui}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CS_OK "Status requester 'Ok'"
@toc SR

Status requester 'Ok'
---------------------

Select 'Ok' to accept the chosen status.

[À]
@endnode

@node CS_CC "Status requester 'Cancel'"
@toc SR

Status requester 'Cancel'
-------------------------

Select 'Cancel' to cancel the status selection.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Address requester
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CD "Change destination requester"
@toc FLEXGUI

Change destination requester
----------------------------

This  is  the  Change  destination  requester.  This is a simple @{" Address " LINK RA}
requester.

It opens with the current address.

@endnode

@node RA "Address requester"
@toc FLEXGUI

Address requester
-----------------

The  Address  requester  is  used  to  select  a  Fido address. The Address
requester looks a bit like:

   ---------- Enter address ---------
   Node    @{"                       " LINK RA_N}@{"N" LINK RA_GN}
   System  @{"                         " LINK RA_SYSTEM}
   Sysop   @{"                         " LINK RA_SYSOP}
   ----------------------------------
   @{"       Ok       " LINK RA_OK}@{"     Cancel     " LINK RA_CC}

The Address requester can be opened using the ARexx command @{b}REQUESTADDRESS@{ub}.
See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node RA_N "Address requester 'Node'"
@toc RA

Address requester 'Node'
------------------------

In  the  'Node'  string  gadget  you  enter a fully qualified Fido address.
Reflex  will  automatically  fill the @{i}System@{ui} and @{i}Sysop@{ui} fields beneath if a
nodelist is available.

[À]
@endnode

@node RA_GN "Address requester 'Node requester'"
@toc RA

Address requester 'Node requester'
----------------------------------

Selecting  this  gadget  will  bring forth the @{" Node requester " LINK RN} for you to
select a Fido address from among a group of nodes.

[À]
@endnode

@node RA_SYSTEM "Address requester 'System'"
@toc RA

Address requester 'System'
--------------------------

This  field  is  automatically filled with the system name when you enter a
new Fido address if the address is found in the available nodelists.

[À]
@endnode

@node RA_SYSOP "Address requester 'Sysop'"
@toc RA

Address requester 'Sysop'
-------------------------

This field is automatically filled with the sysop name when you enter a new
Fido address if the address is found in the available nodelists.

[À]
@endnode

@node RA_OK "Address requester 'Ok'"
@toc RA

Address requester 'Ok'
----------------------

Select 'Ok' to accept the specified address.

[À]
@endnode

@node RA_CC "Address requester 'Cancel'"
@toc RA

Address requester 'Cancel'
--------------------------

Select 'Cancel' to cancel the address selection.

[À]
@endnode

@remark --------------
@remark Node requester
@remark --------------

@node RN "Node requester"
@toc FLEXGUI

Node requester
--------------

The  Node requester is used to select a node among a group of nodes you use
frequently.  These  node  have the @{" Node requester " LINK NE_NR} checkbox ticked in the
@{" Nodebook Editor " LINK NE}. The Node requester looks a bit like:

   --------- Select node --------

   @{"                             " LINK RN_L}

   ------------------------------
   @{"      Ok      " LINK RN_OK}@{"    Cancel    " LINK RN_CC}

The  Node requester is normally opened by clicking one of the small gadgets
to  the right of Node string gadgets. The Node requester can also be opened
using the ARexx command @{b}REQUESTNODE@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node RN_L "Node requester listview"
@toc RN

Node requester listview
-----------------------

The  listview  contains  the nodes that have the @{" Node requester " LINK NE_NR} checkbox
ticked in the Nodebook Editor.

If  Reflex was able to look up the node in one of the available nodelists a
node  will be listed as "<system name>, <address>". Otherwise the node will
be listed in the listview as "<address>".

The  listview  marker is moved up and down using the cursor keys. Selection
is done by double clicking, hitting return or clicking the 'Ok' button.

[À]
@endnode

@node RN_OK "Node requester 'Ok'"
@toc RN

Node requester 'Ok'
-------------------

Selecting  the  'Ok'  button  means you accept the chosen node for whatever
purpose the Node requester was opened.

[À]
@endnode

@node RN_CC "Node requester 'Cancel'"
@toc RN

Node requester 'Cancel'
-----------------------

If  you select 'Cancel' you cancel the selection of one of the nodes in the
listview.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Freq requester
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node FR "Freq requester"
@FLEXGUI

Freq requester
--------------

In the Freq requester you select the files to attach to another system. The
Freq requester looks a bit like:

   ------ Receiving system ------
   Node     @{"                  " LINK FR_N}@{"N" LINK FR_NR}
   System   @{"                    " LINK FR_SYSTEM}
   Sysop    @{"                    " LINK FR_SYSOP}
   --------- Request(s) ---------

            @{"                    " LINK FR_L}

            @{"      Delete        " LINK FR_D}
   Request  @{"                    " LINK FR_F}
   -----------------------------
   @{"      Ok      " LINK FR_OK}@{"    Cancel    " LINK FR_CC}

You  use  the  Freq requester to request files at other systems. You simply
choose  the  address  of  the system at which you will be requesting files;
then you enter the files to request; and finally 'Ok' to actually write the
request to the outbound directory.

You  must  leave  the  requester  via  the  @{" 'Ok' button " LINK AT_OK} for the files to
actually  be  requested.  To cancel the request of the files just click the
@{" 'Cancel' button " LINK AT_CC}.

The  Freq  requester will open with the address of the current entry in the
listview - that is naturally if the current entry has a valid Fido address.

If  you  prefer the Freq requester to open with an empty node string gadget
you  can  use  an  '_Freq.flex' ARexx script that will be executed when you
select  the  'Freq' button in the main listview. In the '_Freq.flex' script
you  will  use  the REQUESTFREQ ARexx command to invoke the Freq requester.
Please refer to the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC} for more information about using
ARexx.

The  Freq  requester  is  either  opened from the 'Freq' button in the main
window or by using the REQUESTFREQ ARexx command.

ARexx commands and scripts are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_N "Freq requester 'Node'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'Node'
---------------------

In  the  'Node'  string  gadget you enter the Fido address of the system at
which you want to request files.

If you opened the Freq requester using the 'Freq' button in the main window
this  string gadget will be filled with the address of the current entry in
the listview if the entry has a valid Fido address.

Is  Reflex  able  to  find  the  system in the nodelist it will fill in the
System and Sysop field in the requester.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_SYSTEM "Freq requester 'System'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'System'
-----------------------

This  field will hold the system name of the system specified in the 'Node'
gadget above.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_SYSOP "Freq requester 'Sysop'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'Sysop'
----------------------

This  field  will hold the sysop name of the system specified in the 'Node'
gadget above.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_NR "Freq requester 'Node requester'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'Node requester'
-------------------------------

Selecting this gadget will invoke the @{" Node requester " LINK RN} for you to select a
node among those selected within the Nodebook.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_L "Freq requester listview"
@toc FR

Freq requester listview
-----------------------

The  listview  contains  the files you want to request at the other system.
Please  notice, that the listview only contains new requests. Requests made
earlier is @{i}not@{ui} shown in the listview.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_D "Freq requester 'Delete'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'Delete'
-----------------------

Selecting  the  'Delete'  button  will  remove  the  current entry from the
request list.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_F "Freq requester 'Request'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'Request'
------------------------

In  the 'Request' string gadget you enter the filename of the file you want
to request.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_OK "Freq requester 'Ok'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'Ok'
-------------------

Use  the  'Ok'  gadget  to  accept the requests, which will be written to a
request file in your outbound directory.

[À]
@endnode

@node FR_CC "Freq requester 'Cancel'"
@toc FR

Freq requester 'Cancel'
-----------------------

Select  'Cancel' to discard the requests when you decide against requesting
the files.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/Attaching help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CFGA "Attaching configuration window"
@toc FLEXGUI

Attaching configuration window
------------------------------

In  the Attaching configuration window you set the default settings for the
Attach  requester and the ATTACH ARexx command. The Attaching configuration
window looks a bit like:

   ------------- Attributes -------------
   Status @{"G|                            " LINK CFGA_S}
   Action @{"G|                            " LINK CFGA_A}
   -------------- Copying ---------------
   @{"  " LINK CFGA_CO} Copy file to outbound
   ------------ Description -------------
   @{"  " LINK CFGA_AD} Auto attach description
   Description file suffix @{"             " LINK CFGA_DS}
   --------------------------------------
   @{"  " LINK CFGA_AC} Attach file comment
   Attached file comment suffix @{"        " LINK CFGA_CS}
   --------------------------------------
   @{"        Ok        " LINK CFGA_OK}@{"      Cancel      " LINK CFGA_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CFGA_OK}  the changed settings are not saved. They will not be saved
until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

The Attaching configuration window can be open from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}
or using the ARexx command @{b}EDITATTACHING@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

The  settings  configured  in  this  configuration  window  is  the default
settings for the Attach requester and most of these settings can be changed
from within the Attach requester for the current attach.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_S "Attaching configuration 'Status'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Status'
--------------------------------

This  cycle  gadget  is  used  to set the status or flavour of the files to
attach. The flavour is either @{i}Normal@{ui}, @{i}Crash@{ui}, @{i}Hold@{ui} or @{i}Direct@{ui}.

This  status/flavour  is the default status for the @{" Attach requester " LINK AT} and
this setting can naturally be changed from within the Attach requester.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_A "Attaching configuration 'Action'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Action'
--------------------------------

This  cycle gadget is used to set the mailer action of the files to attach.
The  mailer  action  is  either  @{i}No special processing@{ui},  @{i}Truncate to zero@{ui},
@{i}Delete with logging@{ui},   @{i}Delete without loggingt{ui},  or  @{i}No special processing,
allow filenote tagging@{ui}. See your mailer documentation for more information
about these mailer actions.

This mailer action is the default mailer action for the @{" Attach requester " LINK AT}
and this setting can naturally be changed from within the Attach requester.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_CO "Attaching configuration 'Copy file to outbound'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Copy file to outbound'
-----------------------------------------------

If  this  checkbox is ticked Reflex will automatically copy the file to the
outbound directory when attaching the file.

This  is  the  default setting for the @{" Attach requester " LINK AT} and this setting
can naturally be changed from within the Attach requester.

If  a  file  with  a  similar name already exists in the outbound directory
Reflex will not copy the file. The file will still be attached but from its
original  directory. Was the mailer action either @{i}Truncate to zero@{ui}, @{i}Delete
with logging@{ui},  or @{i}Delete without loggingt@{ui} it will be changed to @{i}No special
processing@{ui} to avoid harming innocent files.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_AD "Attaching configuration 'Auto attach description'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Auto attach description'
-------------------------------------------------

Ticking  this  checkbox will instruct Reflex to look for a description file
too  when  attaching  a  file.  Reflex  will  search  for description files
matching the @{" Description file suffix " LINK CFGA_DS}.

The  attached  description  -  if  such  is  found  - will be automatically
attached to the receiving system with the same flavour as the file itself.

This  is  the  default  setting for the @{" Attach requester " LINK AT} and this can be
changed from within the Attach requester.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_DS "Attaching configuration 'Description file suffix'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Description file suffix'
-------------------------------------------------

Is  @{" Auto attach description " LINK CFGA_AD}  ticked Reflex will search for a description
file corresponding to the file to attach.

@{i}Description file suffix@{ui}  is the suffix of the description file which Reflex
will  search  for.  This  is  an  AmigaDOS pattern (see @{" Poll pattern " LINK CFGM_PAT} for
information about patterns). This is only the suffix, i.e. everything after
the last '.' in the filename.

Let's  describe  the  working  of this with an example. We want to attach a
file named

   program.lha

and we have ticked @{i}Auto attach description@{ui}. When Reflex performs the actual
attaching  it in addition of attaching the file will look for a description
file to attach too.

If  the  filename  has  got a suffix, 'lha' in the case with 'program.lha',
this  suffix  will  be  replaced  with the @{i}Description file suffix@{ui}. Is your
@{i}Description file suffix@{ui}

   (readme|desc)

Please  notice,  that  the  '.' before the suffix NOT is in the @{i}Description
file suffix@{ui}.

Reflex will search for description files matching the pattern

   program.(readme|desc)

This means, in this case, that both

   program.readme
   program.desc

are  valid description files for Reflex to attach. Please notice, that only
the first match Reflex finds will be attached.

Is  this  string  gadget  empty Reflex can naturally not find a description
file to auto attach.

You  are  not  able  to  change the description file suffix from within the
@{" Attach requester " LINK AT}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_AC "Attaching configuration 'Attach file comment'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Attach file comment'
---------------------------------------------

If  you ticked @{" Auto attach description " LINK CFGA_AD} and Reflex was unable to locate a
description  file  with  the  @{" Description file suffix " LINK CFGA_DS} ticking the @{i}Attach
file  comment@{ui}  will  instruct  Reflex to look for a file comment and attach
this as the description.

If the attached file has a file comment this will be attached, otherwise no
description  will  be attached. The comment description file will be placed
in  the  outbound directory and will be named the same as the file but with
the  suffix  defined under @{" Attached file comment suffix " LINK CFGA_CS}. Such a @{i}Attached
file comment suffix@{ui} must be specified for Reflex to attach file comments.

This  is  one  of  the  few  settings that can't be changed from within the
@{" Attach requester " LINK AT}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_CS "Attaching configuration 'Attached file comment suffix'"

Attaching configuration 'Attached file comment suffix'
------------------------------------------------------

The  @{i}Attached file comment suffix@{ui}  is the suffix which the description file
will become when Reflex attaches a file comment as the description.

Is the name of the file to attach

  program.lha

and is @{i}Attached file comment suffix@{ui} specified as

  note

then the file comment description file will be named

  program.note

and  will  be  placed  in the outbound directory, attached to the receiving
system and will be deleted by the mailer when it has been sent.

For a file comment to be attached @{" Auto attach description " LINK CFGA_AD} must be ticked
@{i}and@{ui}  Reflex  must  not  find  a description file. Furthermore you must have
ticked  @{" Attach file comment " LINK CFGA_AC}  @{i}and@{ui}  a  suffix  must  be  specified  as the
@{i}Attached file comment suffix@{ui}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_OK "Attaching configuration 'Ok'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Ok'
----------------------------

When you're done and want to keep the changes click in the 'Ok' gadget.

The  changes will be used but are not saved. To save the changes select the
@{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CFGA_CC "Attaching configuration 'Cancel'"
@toc CFGA

Attaching configuration 'Cancel'
--------------------------------

When  you're  done but don't want to keep the changes click in the 'Cancel'
gadget. The changes will be discarded and the old settings will be used.

[À]
@endnode

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@remark Settings/ARexx help
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CFGR "ARexx configuration window"
@toc FLEXGUI

ARexx configuration window
--------------------------

From   the   ARexx  window  you  configure  the  'ARexx'  menu.  The  ARexx
configuration window looks a bit like:

   --------- ARexx menu ----------
   Menu items @{"                   " LINK CFGR_MI}

              @{"  Add   " LINK CFGR_A}@{"  Delete  " LINK CFGR_D}
              @{"       Edit        " LINK CFGR_E}
              @{"   Up   " LINK CFGR_U}@{"   Down   " LINK CFGR_DW}
              @{"       Sort        " LINK CFGR_S}
   -------------------------------
   @{"       Ok      " LINK CFGR_OK}@{"    Cancel    " LINK CFGR_CC}

If  you  have  made  changes  and  leave the  configuration window via the
@{" 'Ok' gadget " LINK CFGR_OK}  the changed settings are not saved. They will not be saved
until you select the @{" 'Save' menu item " LINK FM_SSS} in the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}.

You can - if I remember correctly - add 40 menu items to the 'ARexx' menu.

The  ARexx  configuration window can be opened from the @{" 'Settings' menu " LINK FM_S}
or using the ARexx command @{b}EDITAREXX@{ub}. See the @{" ARexx documentation " LINK AREXXDOC}.

ARexx commands are only available to the @{" registered user " LINK UNREG}.

