@remark ---------------------------------------
@remark other nodes
@remark ---------------------------------------

@node TRITON "Triton"

Triton
------

Triton  is  what  its  author  calls  a GUI creation system. The Triton GUI
creation  system  offers  a very simple way of making pretty font-sensitive
GUIs without having to program using GadTools directly.

Reflex  uses the Triton GUI creation system and therefore you must have the
'triton.library' located in your libs: directory for Reflex to work.

As  of  this  writing  the current version of 'triton.library' is 5.5 - you
will  find  this as the 1.4 release of Triton. A beta of Triton release 2.0
has  been  released  and is included in the Reflex distribution as well - I
use this myself, and I think you should too, but please remember it is only
a beta release.

Several  aspects  can  be  configured through the Triton preference system,
though  this  requires  you  to  be a registered user. If you in the @{" GUI " LINK CGUI}
configuration  chooses  the Triton background the window background will be
selected through the Triton preference systems.

For a user Triton is fully usable without registering, but I will recommend
you  to  register  like me, because you both support the author and further
development @{i}and@{ui} you can use the Triton preference system.

Unlike  other  GUI  libraries,  e.g.  MUI,  Triton  is  small  and fast. It
naturally doesn't offer as much, but is much nicer to work with.

Triton   is   written   by  Stefan  Zeiger  (s.zeiger@laren.rhein-main.de),
Seligenstõdter Weg 24, D-63796 Kahl, Germany.

Without  Triton  Reflex  would  probably  have  looked  lousy  and  had  no
configuration GUIs - and more important - would never had been finished.

[À]
@endnode

@node TRAPDOOR "TrapDoor"

TrapDoor
--------

TrapDoor  is  probably  the  most widely used mailer on the Amiga. I myself
find  it rather good although I haven't really tried anything else. Being a
registered user TrapDoor suits me quite well.

TrapDoor  is  written  by  Maximilian Hantsch (max@madvie.co.at) and Martin
Laubach  (mjl@alison.co.at),  Matzleinsdorfer  Platz 3-4/3/10, A-1050 Wien,
Austria.

[À]
@endnode

@node GMS "GMS"

GMS
---

Like  @{" TrapDoor " LINK TRAPDOOR}  GMS is a mailer. Unlike TrapDoor I've been told that GMS
offers  hydra which should be bi-directional transfer. Rumour says that the
next version of TrapDoor will offer too.

I  know  several  GMS  users  and  they are all quite satisfied with GMS. I
really don't know who has written GMS.

[À]
@endnode

@node CONFIG "Configuration file"

Configuration file
------------------

Reflex  will  save  its  configuration file to 'PROGDIR:'. If this location
doesn't suit you, you may move the configuration file to 'MAIL:' instead.

If  Reflex  doesn't find the configuration file in 'PROGDIR:' but rather in
'MAIL:'  Reflex  will  then save the configuration file to 'MAIL:' when you
later save the configuration.

[À]
@endnode

@node AREXXPORT "ARexx port"

ARexx port
----------

Reflex  has  naturally  got  an  ARexx port, called 'REFLEX'. ARexx is only
available to the @{" registered " LINK REGISTER} users of Reflex.

Reflex  uses  the  @{" EasyREXX " LINK EASYREXX}  interface  for  its  ARexx  port. Therefore
'easyrexx.library' must be available in you 'libs:' directory.

The  ARexx  port and the more than 100 ARexx commands are documented in the
'Reflex.ARexx.doc' file included in the Reflex distribution.

The  purpose of the ARexx port is to make available a powerful interface to
the  users.  An  interface  to  the  features and possibilities that Reflex
offers.

With more than 100 ARexx commands most needs should be fulfilled.

Using  the ARexx port gives you the possibility of tailoring Reflex to your
system  and  needs  and  performing  the  specific tasks you like Reflex to
perform unattended.

Reflex  has  got  a very important feature and that is ARexx locking. ARexx
locking  means  you  lock the ARexx port so only your script can access the
port.  Two  ARexx  scripts being executed at the same time could cause some
nasty  consequences  - ARexx locking prevents this. ARexx locking should be
used  by  all scripts. Please read the 'OWNERSHIP' section and the commands
associated with ARexx locking in the ARexx documentation.

If  you  are to write ARexx scripts I recommend you read the --background--
part of the 'Reflex.ARexx.doc' before starting.

[À]
@endnode

@node AREXXDOC "ARexx documentation"

ARexx documentation
-------------------

For  more  information please refer to the 'Reflex.ARexx.doc' file included
in the Reflex distribution.

For at bit more information see @{"  " LINK AREXXPORT}.

ARexx is only available to @{" registered " LINK REGISTER} users.

[À]
@endnode

@node _AREXX "'_<gadget>.flex' scripts"

'_<gadget>.flex' scripts
------------------------

A  very  important feature of Reflex is the '_<gadget>.flex' scripts. These
scripts are ARexx scripts that Reflex will execute when you select a gadget
in the main window instead of the default action of Reflex.

Using  such scripts you can have Reflex act differently. If you for example
have  made  an '_Delete.flex' script you can make the script delete entries
in  the  outbound  list  without  displaying  the  safety requesters Reflex
normally prompts you with.

'_<gadget>.flex' scripts are available for all buttons in the main window:

Main window button        Name of '_<gadget>.flex' script
---------------------------------------------------------
@{"        Info        " LINK F_I}     _Info.flex
@{"       Delete       " LINK F_D}     _Delete.flex
@{"       Attach       " LINK F_A}     _Attach.flex
@{"        Freq        " LINK F_F}     _Freq.flex
@{"    Change Status   " LINK F_CS}     _ChangeStatus.flex
@{" Change Destination " LINK F_CD}     _ChangeDestination.flex
@{"        Poll        " LINK F_P}     _Poll.flex
@{"     Maintenance    " LINK F_M}     _Maintenance.flex
@{"       Rescan       " LINK F_R}     _Rescan.flex
@{"        Quit        " LINK F_Q}     _Quit.flex

In  addition  to these '_<gadget>.flex' scripts Reflex will also attempt to
execute  a  '_<gadget>.flex'  script  when you double click an entry in the
main window listview:

Main window listview      Name of '_<gadget>.flex' script
---------------------------------------------------------
@{"                    " LINK F_L}     _Listview.flex

A  '_<gadget>.flex'  script  is  also  attached  to  two  menu items of the
'Project' menu:

Menu item                 Name of '_<gadget>.flex' script
---------------------------------------------------------
@{"        Print       " LINK FM_PP}     _Print.flex
@{"        Quit        " LINK FM_PQ}     _Quit.flex

The  menu  item 'Quit' and the button 'Quit' have the same '_<gadget>.flex'
script attached.

'_<gadget>.flex' scripts must be located in the @{" ARexx directory " LINK CFGF_AD}.

ARexx and '_<gadget>.flex' scripts are only available to the @{" registered " LINK REGISTER}
user.

[À]
@endnode

@node KEYFILE "Keyfile"

Keyfile
-------

To use Reflex to its full extent a keyfile is needed. A keyfile unlocks the
features disabled in the unregistered evaluation version.

To obtain a keyfile you will have to @{" register " LINK REGISTER}. When I have received your
registration  you will receive the keyfile within a short time. The keyfile
must  be  named  'Reflex.key'  and  must  be  placed  either in a directory
specified  in  the KEYPATH environment variable, 'PROGDIR:' or 's:'. Reflex
will  search  for  the  keyfile  in  the same order as the directories were
mentioned.

Do  not  in  anyway  modify  the keyfile. The keyfile contains code that is
being  executed,  and  it  might  therefore  have  severe  consequences  if
something is wrong within the keyfile.

[À]
@endnode

