@node TRAPLIST "TrapList"

TrapList
--------

TrapList  is  the  nodelist  compiler supplied with the @{" TrapDoor " LINK TRAPDOOR} mailer.
Access  to  the  TrapList  compiled  nodelists  is done through the runtime
shared    library,    'traplist.library'.    Lots   of   applications   use
'traplist.library',  e.g.  Spot,  TrapDoor, Mail Manager, and GMS all to my
knowledge  use  'traplist.library'. Therefore you probably already have the
'traplist.library' installed.

Naturally  Reflex  also supports TrapList compiled nodelists. Actually some
features  of  Reflex requires the 'traplist.library' to be installed in you
'libs:' directory.

As of this writing the current version of 'traplist.library' is 5.4.

TrapList   and   'traplist.library'   are  written  by  Maximilian  Hantsch
(max@madvie.co.at)  and  Martin Laubach (mjl@alison.co.at), Matzleinsdorfer
Platz 3-4/3/10, A-1050 Wien, Austria.

[À]
@endnode

@node REQTOOLS "ReqTools"

"ReqTools"
----------

ReqTools  is  the  most  widely used requester library on the Amiga. It has
existed for years. The 'reqtools.library' gives a programmer easy access to
a wide variety of requesters.

As  of  this writing the current version of 'reqtools.library' is 38.1413 -
you  will  find  this as the 2.5 release of ReqTools. The last version Nico
did was version 38.1266 - release 2.2c of ReqTools.

ReqTools  was original written by Nico Franþois (nico@augfl.be), Corbielaan
13,  B-3060  Bertem,  Belgium. As of version 2.3 the programming is done by
Magnus  Holmgren  (cmh@lls.se),  Kvarnbergsvõgen  5,  S-444 47 Stenungsund,
Sweden.

[À]
@endnode

@node EASYREXX "EasyREXX"

EasyREXX
--------

EasyREXX  is  a  runtime  shared  library,  'easyrexx.library'  that  gives
programmers  a  very  easy  way  of  implementing  an  ARexx  port in their
programs. The EasyREXX distribution comes along with an ARexx designer that
helps  you  make  the  necessary  code  to  implement an ARexx port and the
handling  of  the ARexx interface - I haven't used this, so I don't know if
this designer is any good.

As  of  this writing the current version of 'easyrexx.library' is 3.0 - you
can  find this as the 3.2 distribution of EasyREXX (distribution 3.0 to 3.2
is  probably  just  updates  of  the  EasyREXX  designer and not the actual
library).

EasyREXX  is  written by Ketil Hunn (ketil@lis.pitt.edu), 6629 Wilkins Ave,
Pittsburgh, PA 15217, U.S.A. Ketil is currently a student at the University
of  Pittsburgh  so  I do not know how long the above address will be valid.
He's a norwegian, poor guy.

[À]
@endnode

@node SORTLIST "SortList"

SortList
--------

SortList  is  a  linkable  library containing functions to sort Exec lists.
SortList is written by Preben Nielsen.

Reflex  uses  the  SortList  functions  for  sorting  its  different lists.
Currently Reflex also requires @{" traplist.library " LINK TRAPLIST} to sort node numbers.

Where to find SortList I do not know. Mail me if you need it. The version I
have  used  in Reflex had to be slightly altered binary to work with SAS/C.
Thanks to Preben for helping me with this.

Prebens Fido address is 2:235/314.106 if you want to contact him.

[À]
@endnode

@node QUICKHELP "QuickHelp"

Triton QuickHelp
----------------

Triton  QuickHelp  is  a  feature that @{" Triton " LINK TRITON}  offers. When you move the
mouse  pointer  to  a  gadgets  a  small  window with a little text will be
displayed.  When  you  remove  the  pointer from the gadget the window will
disappear.

QuickHelp  is  very  useful but can also be quite annoying. Afterall one do
not need to be told what the main window 'Poll' gadget do when one has been
using Reflex for several month.

Therefore  you  are  able  to  turn  QuickHelp  on  and  off  in the @{" GUI " LINK CGUI}
configuration window.

[À]
@endnode

@node TRANSLATIONS "Catalog translations"

Catalog translations
--------------------

Currently  only  the  built-in  English  language,  Danish  and  Swedish is
supported.  But  since  Reflex  uses  'locale.library' for its localization
translations to other languages are quite easy.

In  the 'catalog' directory in the Reflex distribution you will find a file
named  'Reflex.cd'.  This is the catalog description file. Using this and a
program  like  CatComp you can generate a catalog translation file in which
you  put  the  translations.  After you have done this you can have CatComp
generate a 'Reflex.catalog' to support your language.

The catalog description file contains a lot of additional information which
I  hope  will  help  the translator. There might actually be a bit too much
information.

When  you  have made a translation please send the catalog translation file
(e.g.  'deutsch.ct')  to  me.  Do not send the catalogs since I will myself
generate  the  actual  catalogs from the catalog translation files you send
me.  I  will  then include both the generated catalog and probably also the
catalog translation file with the next Reflex distribution.

Feel  free  to  contact  me  if  you've  got  any  questions  regarding the
translation.

I  recommend you @{" contact me " LINK AUTHOR} before you start translating all the strings
in   the  catalog  description  file.  Somebody  else  might  already  have
translated  Reflex to your language and then all your work would be a waste
of time.

People  with  an  e-mail address is preferred for ease of contact for quick
localization of new strings for new versions - if new versions ever will be
released.

If  you  make a translation please have a look at the file "Install Reflex"
located in the "Install/Workbench_2.1+" drawer in the distribution archive.
This  file  also needs a section localized to your language. Currently only
English,  Danish and Swedish is available, but the "Install Reflex" file is
prepared  for  german,  spanish,  french,  italian,  dutch,  norwegian, and
portugues  with  a  section for each language. Sections for other languages
can naturally be made if someone writes them.

Danish translation is done by Peter Kµrsaa (2:238/49).

Swedish translation is done by Magnus Holmgren (cmh@lls.se).

[À]
@endnode

@node REGISTER "How to register"

How to register
---------------

After  a  30  day  period  of  evaluation  you  ought to register. You will
most  probably  have  noticed,  that  certain  features  is disabled in the
@{" unregistered version " LINK UNREG}. To enable these features you must register.

To  register  print  out  the  registration  form you will find in the file
'Reflex.regform',  or  submit  the  necessary  information  in  another way
(please write legible). The information needed is:

   1.  Your name
   2.  Your mailing address
   3.  Country
   4.  Your phonenumber (not compulsory)
   5.  Your Fido address and other FTN addresses (not compulsory)
   6.  E-mail addresses (not compulsory)
   7.  Your birthday (day, month and year)
   8.  Any other information you want to tell me

Put  the form or letter in an envelope along with the registration fee. The
registration  fee  is  150 DKK (Danish kroner). The registration fee can be
submitted in different ways:

   1.  Cash  in  different currencies. The following currencies is accepted
       and the amount necessary in that currency:

        150 DKK (Danish kroner)
        200 SEK (Swedish kroner)
        200 NOK (Norwegian kroner)
         20 GBP (British pounds)
         40 DEM (German marks)
         25 USD (American dollars)
        150 FRF (French francs)
        900 BEF (Belgian francs)
         40 CHF (Swiss francs)
         45 NLG (Dutch gulden)
        120 FIM (Finnish marks)
        300 ATS (Austrian schillings)
         35 CAD (Canadian dollars)
         20 IEP (Irish punts)
         35 AUD (Australian dollars)
         40 NZD (Dollars from New Zealand - (New Zealandic dollars?))

       Only notes are accepted. Only the above currencies is accepted. Cash
       is mailed at your own risk.

   2.  A EuroCheck on 150 Danish kroner (DKK). EuroChecks are only accepted
       in DKK. Payable to 'Uffe Holst Christiansen'.

   3.  A  cheque  on  150  Danish kroner (DKK) drawn on a Danish bank. Only
       cheques in DKK are accepted. Only cheques drawn on a Danish bank are
       accepted. Payable to 'Uffe Holst Christiansen'.

   4.  A wire bank transfer:

          Account holder  : Uffe Holst Christiansen
          Account number  : 5470-1541947
          Bank SWIFT code : FBBKDKKK
          Bank name       : Forstµdernes Bank
                            Glostrup Centret 38
                            DK 2600 Glostrup
                            Denmark

Finally you must decide how you want to receive the keyfile.

   1. On a disk mailed to your mailing address.

   2. Sent  to  you  by  e-mail. Keyfiles are sent PGP encrypted, so I will
      need  your PGP public key. Mail your PGP public key to me either on a
      disk along with the shareware fee or to my e-mail address (as long as
      it is valid).

      To  decrypt  your  keyfile  upon  receipt you will need @{" my PGP key " LINK PGP}
      which you find elsewhere in this document.

Close the envelope and mail the letter. My address is

