@node ENTRYTYPES "Outbound directory entry types"

Outbound directory entry types
------------------------------

Many  types  of  files  may  exist  in  the outbound directory. When Reflex
rescans  your  outbound  directory  files and flow file contents are put in
nine different groups.

 - Compressed mail bundles (or ARCMail) are normal Fido mail listed in flow
   files. These files are recognised by Reflex by having the following file
   pattern "zone.net.node.point.(mo|tu|we|th|fr|sa|su)[0-9]".

 - Uncompressed mail listed in flow files (or mail packets) are normal Fido
   mail  PKTs  that  are listed in flowfiles. These files are recognised by
   Reflex  by  having  the  following  file  pattern  "[0-9a-f].pkt", where
   [0-9a-f] is repeated a total of eight times.

 - Attached  files.  These  are  file attaches, i.e. others files than mail
   listed   in   flow   files.   This  could  for  example  be  files  like
   "Reflex10.lha".

 - Flow  file entries of missing files. This is flow file listings of files
   that  Reflex  is unable to locate according to its path it's listed with
   in the flow file.

 - Uncompressed mail (or 4D mail packets) are Fido mail packets. These will
   normally be mail to be crashed to other systems. Reflex recognises these
   files by the file pattern "zone.net.node.point.(O|C|H|D)UT".

 - File requests.  These are the files that you will be requesting at other
   systems. Listed in "zone.net.node.point.REQ" files.

 - Orphan  files.  This  is files found in the outbound directory which are
   not listed in any flow files or in any other way are destined to another
   system.

 - Empty  files.  This  is  actually orphan files, but they differ from the
   orphan  files  by  having  a  filesize  of  zero.  These files are often
   truncated mail bundles.

 - Requests  at  your  system.  When other people is doing requests at your
   system  normally  a  "zone.net.node.point.RLO"  file is generated. Files
   listed in such a "flow file" is of this type.

[À]
@endnode

@node INTRODUCTION "Introduction"

Introduction
------------

Have  you  ever looked at your outbound directory? Most certainly you have.
It's  scattered  with  flow  files  for  your  points,  flow files for your
uplinks,  compressed  mail  bundles,  messages you have forgotten, messages
that were to be crashed days ago, file requests, truncated mail bundles and
lots of other files.

You've  probably ended with some small utilities and scripts that helps you
maintain  your  outbound directory. But still it's a tedious job and you're
probably  more  or less annoyed every time you take a look at your outbound
directory.

The  answer  to  your  prayers  has  arrived. It's an outbound manager. The
outbound  manager  hopefully  combines  most of your needs when it comes to
maintaining  your  outbound  directory.  At  the  same  time it gives you a
distinct overview of the files in your outbound directory.

Reflex is such an outbound manager.

In  the  summer  of  1994  I maintained my boss' mail system for two months
running on three 286 PCs all booting on a Novell server. The mailer he used
was  Portal  of  Power  which  in  my  opinion  probably is the best mailer
available  for  the  PC.  Portal of Power had an built-in outbound manager.
When  I  returned  to  my Amiga I missed the outbound manager even though I
only  was  running  a  small  point  system with one FidoNet uplink and one
AmigaNet  uplink,  and  compared  to  my boss' system with four uplinks and
probably  more than fifty points in the different nets, one could certainly
easily  get  an  overview  of my outbound directory - but I still missed an
outbound manager.

In  May  1995  I  took  a look at Triton - the GUI creation system - and my
first  test  GUI  looked more or less like the Reflex main window. I made a
quick  dirty  outbound  scan  and  showed it to one of my friends running a
Amiga  node  system.  He  liked it a lot (don't know why, since he couldn't
close  the GUI, and the rescan routine screwed up his memory, and it didn't
have a version string) and wanted it finished right away.

Finally a year later Reflex is now finished and is made available to you.

From  the  Reflex main window you can delete files, attach files, make file
requests,  change  flavour  or  destination  of  the  files in the outbound
directory,  and  you  can directly launch you mailer simply by clicking the
'Poll' button. WOW!

Furthermore Reflex can be configured in many ways and by using the built-in
ARexx  port  Reflex  can  be  a  really  powerful  utility  running  in the
background maintaining your outbound directory files.

Hope you like Reflex.

[À]
@endnode

@node INSTALLATION "Installation"

Installation
------------

Installation  is  very simple. Just use the supplied Installer script. This
requires  the  Installer  utility.  Installer is not included in the Reflex
distribution.

If  you  have  Workbench  2.1,  3.0 or higher you'll find Installer on your
Workbench installation disks and most probably already have it somewhere in
your command path. Installer is also available on Aminet.

To install Reflex manually:

 - copy the runtime shared libraries:

      'libs/easyrexx.library'
      'libs/reqtools.library'
      'libs/traplist.library'
      'libs/triton.library'

   to  your  LIBS:  directory.  Remember  to check if you actually have got
   newer  versions  of  these  libraries installed already. Use the command
   'Version' to check the library versions of your installed libraries. The
   file  'libs/README.libraries'  will  list  the  library  versions of the
   supplied libraries in the Reflex distribution.

 - Create  a drawer for Reflex on your harddisk named 'Reflex' and drag the
   files 'Reflex', 'Reflex.guide', 'Reflex.ARexx.doc', 'Reflex.regform' and
   'README' to it.

 - Create  a  drawer  for  the  ARexx scripts in your REXX: directory named
   'Reflex' and copy the supplied ARexx scripts to it.

The  manual  installation  described  above  will not include localization.
Localization  is  only  available  for  Workbench  2.1+  and  then you most
certainly have got the Installer utility.

[À]
@endnode

@node TRITONBUGS "Triton bugs"

Triton bugs
-----------

Unfortunately  Reflex contains a few bugs and flaws. Some of them is due to
@{" Triton " LINK TRITON} and I really can't do much about this.

Probably  the  worst  Triton bug is, that sometimes the listview isn't wide
enough  even  though  I've told Triton to use the fixed width font and make
the listview the 67 characters wide.

This  can  luckily  be  solved.  My  betatester said I should call this the
Triton  listview  bug  offset.  You  load  your  Reflex  configuration file
'Reflex.cfg' in your editor and find the line:

   MinWidth        67

and increase the number with one, so the line becomes

   MinWidth        68

this  ought  to solve the problem. If not attempt to increse the value with
one more to 69.


Above  the listview is the header 'Address System Filename Status Size' and
unfortunately  I can't force this text to use a fixed width font. Depending
upon  the  font  you use for you Workbench the header might not be centered
above  the  columns in the listview. Sorry about this - I have asked Stefan
for a tag so I can force the text to use the fixed width font.


Triton  doesn't  offer  an  integer  gadget. That's the reason for the ugly
@{" ReqTools " LINK REQTOOLS} integer requester workaround. According to Stefan will the next
release of Triton have an integer gadget. Triton 2.0 beta does offer a sort
of integer gadget (and even Fido address gadget :-) and this will naturally
(!) be implemented as soon as a non-beta of Triton 2.0 is released.


I  had  hoped  it would be possible to press shift-arrow-down when a string
gadget  is  active  to  invoke  for  example  a  file requester or the node
requster.  Unfortunately this isn't possible at the moment with Triton, but
Stefan  has  promised me to make it possible in a future version - well, he
also promised the integer gadget and that's almost a year ago.


If  you  move  the listview by using the mouse and dragbar to the right and
move the list so far that the listview marker disappears it will not appear
again  when  you  start  moving  it  until  it reaches the part of the list
visible in the listview. Stefan says this is fixed for Triton release 2.


Well, Triton isn't the cause for all flaws, see @{" other bugs " LINK OTHERBUGS}.

[À]
@endnode

@node OTHERBUGS "Other bugs"

Other bugs
----------

Apart from the @{" Triton bugs " LINK TRITONBUGS} Reflex is naturally bugfree. Well, that's not
exactly true.

Rescans  fails  if  a file is busy. I really haven't looked much into this,
because  it  requires a total rewrite of the rescan, but I hope to solve it
in  a  future  version  (if I get time to make a future version). But don't
expect too much.


Any other bugs? Report to @{" me " LINK AUTHOR}.

[À]
@endnode

@node CONFIGURATION "Configuration"

Configuration
-------------

The  configuration  Reflex  is  quite simple. At the initial startup Reflex
will  ask  a  few  questions  configuring  the  most  basic settings. These
settings is enough for Reflex to function properly.

The configation is saved to a @{" configuration file " LINK CONFIG}.

Further configuration is made through the eight configuration windows.

The  @{" Files " LINK CFGF}  configuration  window  is  the window in which you specifies
paths to outbound directory, nodelist directory etc.

In the @{" Mailer " LINK CFGM} configuration window you specifies settings concerning the
interaction with you mailer.

The  @{" GUI " LINK CGUI}  configuration is used for settings concerning the graphic user
interface.

In  the  @{" General " LINK CFGG}  configuration window you set hotkeys and some settings
concerning the rescanning.

In  the  @{" Deletion " LINK DCFG} configuration window you tell Reflex what files it may
automatically delete when performing maintenances.

The  @{" Attaching " LINK CFGA}  configuration  window  is  used  for setting the default
settings for the @{" Attach " LINK AT} requester.

In the @{" Nodebook " LINK CFGN} you set certain settings for certain nodes.

Finally  the  @{" ARexx " LINK CFGR}  configuration  window  is  used for configuring the 
'ARexx' menu.

All the configuration windows are opened through the 'Settings' menu.

[À]
@endnode

@node SUPPORT "Support"

Support
-------

Reflex  is  quite easy to use and I hope most can use Reflex without having
any  problems. Alas, some might experience some problems. Therefore support
is available in many ways.

A  Fido  echo  named  'REFLEX'  was  once  available,  but the three boards
carrying  it have closed, so... Well, it might reappear so look out for it.
I  hoped  the Reflex echo will become a forum for Reflex folks to help each
other and for exchanging ARexx scripts.

I  can  be  contacted through FidoNet netmail or AmigaNet netmail on one of
the following addresses; 2:236/200.12 or 39:140/103.12.

I've  also  got  an  Internet  e-mail address; d952412@student.dtu.dk. This
address will at least be valid until the summer of 1997 (probably longer).

Last chance is snail mail:

    Uffe Holst Christiansen
    c/o Christiansen
    Strandgaards Alle 11
    DK 3600 Frederikssund
    Denmark

do  not  expect  a  fast reply and I really can't afford to answer too many
letters. Postage in Denmark is in my opinion quite expensive.

Updates?  I  don't  know when if ever. Currently I neither got the time nor
the  interest  for  continue programming on Reflex or any other program. As
soon  as  a  non-beta  version  of  Triton  2.0 is released I will probably
release  a  new  version  that utilizes a few of the features in Triton 2.0
(i.e.  integer  gadget).  I  have also got folders for Reflex planned. With
'folders'  I  mean  the  possibility  of  grouping all entries for a single
system  (especially points) as one single entry in the listview - I already
got  everything concerning folders planned - only in my head unfortunately,
so  the implementation might take some time. A Triton 2.0 release of Reflex
might be delayed because I start implementing these folders.

Currently  Reflex  requires traplist.library for some of its features. In a
future  release  I hope I will have had the time to removed this dependency
for most of these features. I myself find it unreasonable that the listview
is unsorted if traplist.library is unavailable and that some ARexx commands
are useless.

Futhermore  I  intend  to  make my own ARexx port - more or less a clone of
EasyREXX.  I've  already  once  made  a  very  simple ARexx port for a test
program  -  it  shouldn't  be  that hard to write a port giving me the same
features  that  EasyREXX offers me (actually EasyREXX offers me more than I
need).   A   future   release   will   also   use  asl.library  instead  of
reqtools.library.

Well, that naturally is if a future release ever will be available.

[À]
@endnode

@node AUTHOR "Author information"

Author information
------------------

A few words about myself. I've just turned 26 and I can tell you it's a bit
hard to become that old and realise that you really haven't gotten anywhere
in your life - yet.

After highschool I started to study chemical engineering at the Engineering
Academy of Denmark. Chemical engineering is actually quite interesting, you
know  -  inorganic  and  organic  chemistry, biochemistry, mathmatics, unit
operations,  physical chemistry etc. etc. etc. But I had a problem, I found
the  chemical  engineering quite interesting but not enough interesting for
me to want to actually end being a chemical engineer.

After  a  couple  of  years - actually quite a few years - I had long known
that  my  choice  of  chemical  engineering  was a wrong choice, and when I
suddenly  knew  what I wanted to become it really wasn't a hard decision to
quit my chemical engineering study.

So  right  now I've studied civil engineering at the Engineering Academy of
Denmark  (which  in  the  meantime  has  become  a  part  of  the Technical
University of Denmark) for more than a year, and I'm still quite satisfied.

Computers  and  I.  I've had an Amiga for close to eight years. Currently I
have an Amiga 4000/030 - too slow and not enough memory, but I can't afford
to upgrade it so I guess I have to live with it. I've been programming in C
for  four  years.  I'm  really  a  lousy  programmer.  I'm so slow, but the
programs  I  make  are quite user-friendly - both for the users and for the
system.  A  decent  programmer  could probably make them 10 % smaller - and
faster  too.  Apart  from C I've also been programming Comal-80, C64 BASIC,
AmigaBASIC,  ISO-Pascal,  Turbo  Pascal,  Borland  C,  Prolog and naturally
AmigaOS  scripts  -  on  the other hand I almost haven't touched ARexx. And
lately I've also looked into Installer LISP.

Recently  I  also  bought  an  old A2000, because my A4000 wont run the old
demos  I loved like Hardwired and State of the Art. Most demos are actually
not worth looking at. Both my Amigas are naturally hooked up to my stereo.

Lately  I've  also  bought a used PC (486DX2 66 MHz), because I need to run
WordPerfect 5.1. The Windows installed on it when I bought it I've deleted.
Poof - and gone it was.

Apart  from  my  computer,  my programming and my FidoNet, I spend too much
time  with  my  friends drinking beer (and wine) and the like, listening to
music  and having fun. Not to mention the time I use talking with my friend
on  the  phone. I really ought to use the time doing my homework instead if
I'm ever to get a degree.

I can be contacted at my parents address:

   Uffe Holst Christiansen
   c/o Christiansen
   Strandgaards Alle 11
   DK 3600 Frederikssund
   Denmark

or via some sort of electronic mail:

   FidoNet  : 2:236/200.12
   AmigaNet : 39:140/103.12
   Internet : d952412@student.dtu.dk  (at least valid until summer 1997)

@{" My PGP public key " LINK PGP}.

[À]
@endnode

@node FEATURES "Feature"

Features
--------

Reflex features include:

 > FidoNet 4D outbound directory manipulating tool.

 > Reflex gives you an easy overview and control of files in your outbound
   directory.

 > Reflex is a Commodities Exchange application.

 > Reflex is a Triton GUI application.

 > Reflex supports the TrapList nodelist.

 > ARexx port through the EasyREXX interface. Reflex currently supports
   more than 100 ARexx commands.

 > Launch your mailer directly from Reflex with a simple keystroke
   - being it asynchronously or synchronously.

 > AmigaGuide online help and Triton QuickHelp available. The guide is
   throughly cross-referenced. The online help is context sensitive.

 > Progress requesters at time consuming operations (optional).

 > Configurable height of outbound directory listview.

 > Changeable backgrounds for windows and requesters gives you a GUI to
   your liking.

 > Reflex opens on any public screen.

 > Hotkeys to popup, rescan and quit.

 > Operation of main window gadgets are configurable through ARexx.

 > Maintenance deletes orphan files (files in outbound directory not
   destined to another system), empty files (normally mail bundles
   truncated by to zero the mailer) and/or flow file entries of missing
   files. Everything is naturally optional.

 > Automatic maintenance at each rescan (optional) or manual maintenance
   from a gadget.

 > Attach files to other systems directly from Reflex using the Reflex
   Attach requester. Multiple files are selected at once through a ReqTools
   multiselect requester.

 > Request files from other systems directly from Reflex using the Reflex
   Freq requester.

 > Delete files in outbound directory. Reflex automatic handles and updates
   your flow files.

 > Change the destination of files in the outbound directory, e.g. this can
   be used for host routing of netmails. Reflex automatic handles and
   updates your flow files.

 > Change the flavour (normal, crash, hold, direct) of files in the
   outbound directory. Reflex automatic handles and updates your flow
   files.

 > Nodebook (telephone book clone) gives you easy access to systems you
   often has sessions with.

   À Through the Nodebook you can force Reflex to call another address
     or phone number when launching the mailer. E.g. to force your mailer
     to call the receivers ISDN line even though the mail is address to the
     normal modem line.

   À Special settings for the mailer for this system, e.g. BAUD 14400.

   À Prevent calls to a system.

   À Change session passwords (through TrapList) from within Reflex.

 > Reflex is fully localized. Currently only English and Danish.

 > Thoroughly tested before public release.

 > @{" Shareware " LINK UNREG} - a few features only available in the registered version

 > and more...

[À]
@endnode

